<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat's Says Israeli Sanctions Lead to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 14 (Xinhua) -- In his first comments
following the visit of United States peace envoy Dennis Ross,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat today warned that the continued
Israeli sanctions would lead to disaster.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of Jewish and Arab members of Israel's
Hadash Party in Ramallah, Arafat accused Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu of fighting the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) instead of terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that the Israeli sanctions, imposed after the July
30 suicide bombings in Jerusalem which killed 16 people,
inflicted tremendous sufferings to the Palestinian people. He
estimated that 100,000 Palestinian workers are not paid due to
Israel's halt of transferring the 14 million-U.S. dollar tax
revenues.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader vowed that none can humiliate the
Palestinian people, who would never be forced to kneel down.
</P>
<P>
Later in a meeting in Nablus with visiting Israeli opposition
Labor lawmaker Yossi Beilin, Arafat downplayed the results of
Ross' just-concluded shuttle mission to the region.
</P>
<P>
He said he was not optimistic about the situation following
Ross' visit, but added he was looking forward to the pending
visit by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's comments reflected his unsatisfaction with Ross, who
focused his attention on pressuring the PNA to fight terrorism
while failing to persuade Israel to lift the sanctions against
the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return to Washington after his fifth meeting with
Arafat in Ramallah Wednesday night, Ross claimed he had succeeded
in opening a new beginning for reviving the stalled
Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
Ross described his major achievement as having managed to
persuade the PNA to renew security cooperation with Israel under a
mechanism, in which U.S. officials from the Central Intelligence
Agency will participate and monitor the Israeli-Palestinian
security efforts in fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials have expressed regret about Ross'
one-sided position in favor of Israel's security needs, while
refraining from exerting more pressure on Israel to lift
sanctions against the Palestinians. Senior Palestinian negotiator
Nabil Shaath said Ross was returning "empty-handed" because of
his failure to lift the Israeli sanctions.
</P>
<P>
One concrete result of Ross' mission seemed to be that he had
paved the way for Albright's much-expected first visit to the
Middle East to promote the ill-fated peace process.
</P>
<P>
Before Ross' visit, Albright made it clear that her visit was
conditional on Ross' success in renewing the Israeli-Palestinian
security cooperation, which Ross claimed having been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media reports expected Albright to visit the region in
early weeks of September, and before then Ross would likely return
here to prepare for her trip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
