<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Condemns Arson in Market Stalls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba today condemned the burning of the old Soweto market
stalls, saying it was the work of Zambia's enemies and that the
government had nothing to do with the arson.
</P>
<P>
The burning is an act of dogs and is retrogressive and
criminal, he said.
</P>
<P>
The days when people were political idiots and resolved to
burning property were long gone, he remarked at Soweto market
after touring the section burnt by a mysterious fire on Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The government is trying to find out how many stalls was
destroyed to see how the victims of the burned stalls could be
assisted by the state.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba urged his countrymen to be alert and guard against
such criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
He assured the marketeers that the government has every
intention to build new structures behind the newly-opened Lusaka
city market.
</P>
<P>
Street vendors should not be chased from the streets unless an
alternative place is found for them to operate from, noted the
president.
</P>
<P>
The burning of the stalls triggered off riots on Wednesday in
the capital city. More than 60 people were arrested and dozens
of others injured in the clashes between policemen and vendors
who went on rampage in protest against the arson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
