<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Starts Oil Pumping Through Iraqi-Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish oil company BOTAS said
that Iraq today started to pump oil through Baku-Ceyhan oil
pipeline under the oil-for-food deal with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
A BOTAS statement said that pumping of crude oil started in
Iraq at 10:55 local time (07:55 GMT) and the oil was loaded onto
the shipping-tank of BOTAS called Arcadia in the southern
Mediterranean Turkish port of Ceyhan to be shipped to buyers.
</P>
<P>
The shipment is the first in the second phase of U.N.'s
oil-for-food program, which was renewed on June 8, allowing Iraq
to sell another 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over a
six-month period to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
goods.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that 63.7 million barrels of oil were
transferred from Kirkuk oil fields to Ceyhan from last December to
June, the first six-month period of limited oil sale of Iraq
under the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the 30 million barrels of Iraqi oil, which
is planned to be sold by the end of August, will be loaded from
Ceyhan and 1.8 million barrels of this amount will be purchased by
Turkish oil company Tupras, added the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi-Turkish pipeline was closed on August 8, 1990 due to
a U.N. embargo imposed upon Iraq following its invasion of
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
