<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Does Not Rule Out Pre-Election Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today
once again rejected calls by Finance Minister Theo Waigel for an
immediate cabinet reshuffle, but did not rule out the possibility
of personnel changes at a later date.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment I don't see any reason for a reshuffle," Kohl,
who is now on vacation in Austria, said in an interview with the
German ZDF television network.
</P>
<P>
But when asked if a cabinet reshuffle was possible before the
German general elections due in September next year, Kohl said,
"I'm completely open on this, but I'd not say now what I'll be
doing before the election."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German newspaper Bild today, Waigel
said a shake-up would strengthen Kohl's 17-member cabinet and
improve his chances to win the next general elections.
</P>
<P>
Suggesting that some ministers did want to leave but were just
trying to hang on to their jobs until the elections, Waigel urged
Kohl to drop them now for the benefit of the whole ruling
coalition.
</P>
<P>
In view of the fact that the government's plan for tax reform
has been foiled by the main opposition Social Democratic Party
(SPD) and the economy is growing too slowly to bring down
Germany's record unemployment, analysts said that a shake-up in
Kohl's cabinet was overdue and could help reverve the government's
steep slide in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
A columnist of the Welt newspaper even questioned whether Kohl
himself had instructed Waigel to speak out, a notion rejected by
Kohl today.
</P>
<P>
According to an Allensbach Institute poll published Wednesday,
Kohl's party continued to trail the SPD in popularity.
</P>
<P>
His Christian Democratic Union (CDU), along with its Bavarian
sister party Christian Social Union (CSU) chaired by Waigel, would
win just 33.4 percent of the vote if elections were held next
Sunday, the poll said. The SPD meanwhile would win 37.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Even without a large-scale reshuffle, Waigel's CSU is still set
to lose one seat in the cabinet at the end of this year when the
Postal Ministry become defunct due to privatization. Some press
reports said that by suggesting a cabinet reshuffle, Waigel was
actually demanding compensation for the loss.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also admitted that the dismantlement of the Postal
Ministry would tilt the balance of his ruling three-party
coalition consisted of the CDU, the CSU and the junior partner Free
Democratic Party (FDP).
</P>
<P>
"We'll have to talk about the issue," Kohl said, but stressed
that it was not a question for public debate.
</P>
<P>
The FDP, which fears that it might be forced to give up one of
its cabinet posts to the CSU, today also reject Waigel's cabinet
reshuffle proposal as "totally unnecessary." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Fighting Erupts in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A defense information officer of
Sierra Leone's military government confirmed today that there was
fresh fighting between west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG)
and government soldiers near the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the British Broadcasting Company, the
fighting erupted Wednesday evening in Lungi, the location of
Sierra Leone's main international airport outside Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The clash broke out as some units of the ECOMOG contingent
based in the airport moved from their positions and tried to use
the cover of darkness to attack government positions around the
airport area at about 10:30 last night, said the officer.
</P>
<P>
Casualty figures have not been released, however, the defense
source said they did not suffer any loss in the fighting despite
the fact that ECOMOG had used heavy weapons such as mortars and
artillery.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, hundreds of local residents fled into
all directions in the long fighting, and a number of houses were
destroyed, most of which were blamed on ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The battle, one of a series of clashes since the May 25 coup,
broke out as many people were hoping talks would restart between
the junta in power and the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) when diplomatic moves were stepped up for
peaceful settlement of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fighting has been continuing around Zimmi,
southeastern Sierra Leone, between government soldiers and their
allies, the former rebel Revolutionary United Front, and the
Kamajors, a group of tradition hunters who have vowed to restore
ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said the Kamajor militiamen were forced
to retreat from a town east of Zimmi, under the attack of
mortars and artillery of their enemies.
</P>
<P>
But a battle field commander was quoted as saying: "We will
never give up this fight. We will fight back."
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that 22 people, including 10 soldiers,
were killed last weekend in clashes around Zimmi, 250 km
southeast of Freetown near the border of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The strategic town, with Liberia just across the Mano River,
has been the scene of heavy fighting between the Kamajors and
government soldiers in the past two weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
