<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Continues to Expel Ethnics From Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Defense Forces
(IDF) and border police forces are continuing to evict about 150
members of the Bedouin Jahalin Tribe from their homeland,
according to a statement of a human rights group today.
</P>
<P>
The tribesmen and women are again being driven out of
their dwelling places where they have lived for 40 years since
their first expulsion shortly after the establishment of the
State of Israel in much of Palestine in 1948, said the
statement issued by the Catholic Human Rights Center for Legal
Resources and Development.
</P>
<P>
"This eviction is another phase in Israel's plan to expand
"Jerusalem" and impose direct Israeli hegemony in 1967-occupied
Palestine. This expulsion will create Jewish territorial
continuity between Jerusalem and the (Jewish) settlement of Ma'ale
Adumim," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement continued, "The Jahalin are being removed to an
alternative -- environmentally hazardous -- site set aside for
the Bedouin. This is an area set aside for the 'natives' because
it is not good enough for the Jews."
</P>
<P>
"This system is based on the same principle 'group areas' used
by the white South African apartheid regime condemned by the
civilized world, according to which each racial group had to live
in its own designated areas," it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement added "The Bedouin are forced to live in
intolerable, inhuman conditions: moving their families into
containers originally designed to house goods, not people, and
into tin shacks which are like ovens under the burning sun."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
