<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Finance Ministry to Pay Debts to Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Finance Ministry has
allocated 2.5 trillion rubles (about 432 million US dollars) to
pay off wage arrears to the military since early this month, a
government official said today.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency quoted head of the federal treasure at
the Finance Ministry Alexander Smirnov as telling the Financial
Information Agency today that the Finance Ministry will earmark
another 1.5 trillion rubles (259 million dollars) for the purpose
by the end of August.
</P>
<P>
The head said he was confident "they will do their part of the
job and pay off the debt to the military before September 1." In
July, the ministry channeled 1.9 trillion rubles (328 million
dollars) for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Smirnov sharply criticized the Defense
Ministry and the local commanders. He said, "The debt amounted to
4.5 trillion rubles (777 million dollars) in early July when we
were preparing the presidential decree on paying off arrears to
the military. Later the figure increased to 5.9 trillion rubles (1
billion dollars). Now the military is saying the amount exceeds
8 trillion (1.38 billion dollars)."
</P>
<P>
"We have the impression the schedule of covering the arrears
exists only for the Finance Ministry, while local commanders often
use the arriving funds as they see fit," he added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that wage arrears to federal defense and law
enforcement agencies reached 7.7 trillion rubles (1.33 billion
dollars) as of July 15, including 4.5 trillion rubles (777 million
dollars) to the Defense Ministry and 0.89 trillion rubles (153.7
million dollars) to the Interior Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
