<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Iraqi PUK Leader Asks Turkey's Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) leader Jalal Talabani today asked Turkey's support
against the "assimilation policy" of the Baghdad government.
</P>
<P>
Talabani, who arrived here Wednesday night for a visit, made
the remarks at a press conference here following his contacts with
Turkish officials.
</P>
<P>
He said that his party will do its best to protect the
security of the Turkish border along northern Iraq, adding that
Turkey has the right to have safe borders.
</P>
<P>
Rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party always
infiltrate into Turkey from northern Iraq to launch attacks on
Turkish military and civil targets in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Talabani added that he had discussed the expansion of
no-fly zone with U.N. officials, not with Turkish officials.
</P>
<P>
In his part, Turkish Foreign Ministry Undersecretary Onur
Oymen said that Turkey attributes importance to continue its ties
with the different parties in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkish diplomatic sources said that Iraqi Kurdistan Democratic
Party (KDP) leader Mesud Barzani is also expected to visit Turkey
in a bid to be informed on the results of the visit by Talabani.
</P>
<P>
A year ago, the PUK fought a war with the Iraqi
government-backed KDP, leading to a U.S. air strikes against the
Iraqi military targets.
</P>
<P>
The two groups signed a peace deal on October 31, 1996 under
the mediation by the U.S., Britain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The northern part of Iraq has been occupied by Kurdish
rebels since the Gulf War in 1991, but it split into rival
zones after the KDP and the PUK began fighting each other in
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
