<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Lead SADC Campaign Against Gender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe was chosen to lead the
campaign to fight domestic violence against women in the Southern
Africa Development Community (SADC) region, a Zimbabwean minister
said today.
</P>
<P>
Thenjiwe Lesabe, Minister of National Affairs, Employment
Creation and Cooperatives, said Zimbabwe was chosen on Tuesday in
Gaborone, Botswana at a meeting of SADC ministers for women's
affairs.
</P>
<P>
"We were chosen because we have a good working relationship
with some of our non-governmental organisations (NGO) which deal
with women's issues and we have asked these NGOs to help us,"she
said.
</P>
<P>
The government would work with the NGOs to come up with a
document to map out a strategy for educating people in the region
about domestic violence against women and other gender issues,
the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Briefing journalists on the outcome of the Gaborone meeting,
Lesabe said the ministers had also approved a declaration on
gender issues which was drafted in Namibia in January this year
at a ministerial meeting of the Council of Women's Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The declaration would now be presented to the meeting of SADC
heads of state in September in Malawi for approval.
</P>
<P>
However, Lesabe could not reveal the details of the
declaration, saying they would only be revealed after they had
been approved.
</P>
<P>
The Gaborone meeting was attended by all SADC countries,
together with representatives of NGOs which deal with gender
issues. 
</P>
