<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Government Suspends Domestic Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has suspended with immediate effect issuing loan guarantees to
public enterprises as a measure of minimizing debt burden.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced today by Minister for Finance
Daniel Yona at a seminar on national debt awareness held in
Arusha, northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Government guarantees issued to public corporations in the
past to cover their borrowings were not properly handled, "thus
resulting in many corporations' default on their obligations and
passing over the burden to the government with serious
implications on the budget", Yona said.
</P>
<P>
According to Yona, many government institutions including
ministries, parastatals have made the government in heavy debt
due to their failure to observe the provisions of the Government
Loans, Guarantees and Grants Act.
</P>
<P>
The government has been necessitated to instruct ministries
and parastatal organizations not to incur any new debts without
prior approval of the cabinet, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Over 30 people including principal secretaries, senior
government officials and heads of public institutions are taking
part in the seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Concerned at Low Aid to Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) was deeply concerned by the all-time low
level of aid to developing countries in 1996, UNICEF chief Carol
Bellamy said today.
</P>
<P>
Despite a steady rise in the number of people with incomes of
less than one dollar a day, overall aid to developing countries
last year tumbled 4 percent in real terms over 1995, to 55.1
billion dollars from 58.9 billion dollars, according to a report
released by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
The OECD reported recently that the Official Development Aid
fell to 0.25 percent of the combined gross national product (GDP)
compared to 0.27 percent in 1995. These are the lowest recorded in
the nearly 30 years since the United Nations set a global aid
target of 0.7 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
"These are more than numbers in an accounting ledger; they
represent a threat to millions of children and to the societies in
which they are growing up. They are a testament to the persistence
of appalling global inequalities -- and to the international
community's shameful failure to eradicate them," she said.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF executive director noted that according to UN
estimates, 1.3 billion people are trapped in absolute poverty --
650 million of them are children -- and their numbers are growing
in every region of the world except South-East Asian and the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
If governments summon the will to earmark 0.7 percent of their
GNP for official development assistance, the additional proceeds
would more than cover the additional 80 billion dollars over 10
years that the UN estimates required to eliminate the worst
aspects of global poverty, she said.
</P>
<P>
The tailspin in aid levels is a direct challenge to the
Convention on the Rights of the Child, which speaks to the plight
of the world's poorest children, and to the work of the United
Nations generally, she said.
</P>
<P>
Private investment and financing are absolutely vital if the
poorest countries are to emerge from poverty, she said, "yet they
cannot attract the private sector without official development
assistance. ODA not only helps these countries weather painful
economic reforms, but enables them to create the social and
economic infrastructure that is vital to development," Bellamy
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
