<HEADLINE> Russian Mir Cosmonauts Back on Earth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian cosmonauts Vasily
Tsibliyev and Alexander Lazutkin today returned to the earth safe
and sound from the troubled space station Mir today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax, during the stay in orbit that lasted
186 days, the cosmonauts made one of three planned space walks,
received two progress cargo craft, carried out a docking with the
U.S. Atlantis space shuttle and conducted a number of experiments
in the areas of biology, geophysics, materials science, ecology
and medicine.
</P>
<P>
It said the most interesting research work in orbit concerned
experiments to study the brain, sleep and human conduct in extreme
situations and zero gravity.
</P>
<P>
However, this expedition was marked by a record number of
incidents on the Mir space station, the flight control center
said.
</P>
<P>
This is the toughest tour in the history of space navigation.
There were 10 incidents within a half year in the space station
Mir.
</P>
<P>
The most serious of the incidents occurred on June 25, when the
Progress M-34 cargo space craft collided with the Spektr
scientific module. The collision made the scientific module
airless and cut power supplies to the orbital space station by
almost 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Expenses on the restoration operation to repair the Spektr
module and the delivery of materials for repair work to the
orbital space station exceeded 100 billion rubles (17.27 million
US dollars), Director General of the Russian Space Agency Yuri
Koptev said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
