<HEADLINE> Member Countries Owe ECOWAS US$ 44.7 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- By June this year, members
countries of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) have owed the sub-regional organization about 44.7
million U.S. Dollars, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an ECOWAS source as saying in Lagos today
that the debt includes arrears of between 3 to 17 years as well
as contributions for 1997.
</P>
<P>
By June this year, among ECOWAS's 16 members, only the Benin
Republic and Cote D'Ivoire have fully paid their contributions,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Liberia has not paid its contributions since 1980, while
Mauritania, Sierra Leone, Gambia and Guinea Bissau have not paid
their contributions for 14, 11, 9 and 8 years, it
said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the ECOWAS secretariat in Lagos has been
suffering difficulties in organizing its activities, and indeed
in paying its staff, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS source noted particularly that this year's ECOWAS
summit, which had been scheduled for this month in Abuja, had
been postponed to an unknown time to allow Liberia's new
president Charles Taylor to attend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
