<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus' total imports (covering imports for home
consumption and imports placed into bonded warehouses) in the
first five months of 1997 fell by 4.5 percent to 765.1 million
Cyprus pounds (about 1,392.48 million U.S. dollars), compared to
801.3 million pounds (about 1,458.37 million dollars) in the same
period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued Thursday by the Department of
Statistics and Research, total exports in the first five months of
1997 decreased by 6.8 percent to 250.7 million pounds (about
456.27 million dollars), compared to 269 million pounds (about
489.58 million dollars) in the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the trade deficit in the same period this year
fell to 514.4 million pounds (936.2 million dollars), compared to
532.4 million pounds (989 million dollars) in the first five
months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's monthly trade deficit totaled 473 million
U.S. dollars in July, the lowest deficit figure since September
1995, according to the latest data of the Central Bureau of
Statistic.
</P>
<P>
Imports reached 2,355 million dollars and exports brought in
some 1,882 million dollars. The monthly deficit compares to 748
million dollars in June this year and 845 million dollars in July
1996.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of this year, the deficit ran to
4,725 million dollars, as against 6,425 million dollars posted for
the equivalent period in 1996. Recent months have seen a steady
increase in imports, after a decline last year coupled with a
slowdown in exports. These trends have been reversed.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government has approved the plan of
constructing a joint Israeli-Jordanian airport at the Jordanian
resort of Aqaba, reported the latest issue of the bi-weekly Israel
Business.
</P>
<P>
The project agreed upon by the two countries include the
establishment of the new airport on the site of the existing
facility at Aqaba with the expansion project costing around 30
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian terminal is to be sited on the Jordanian side of
the border, with the Israeli facility located west of the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
