<HEADLINE> Roundup: Anti-Semitic Incidents on Rise in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- As hundreds of European Nazi
sympathizers are preparing to organize ceremonies Saturday marking
the 10th anniversary of the death of Rudolf Hess, the top aide of
Hitler, two synagogues and two Jewish shops in the southern French
city of Nice were attacked Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Creating the most serious anti-Semitic incident in France since
the Carpentras incident in which several skinheads destroyed tombs
at a Jewish cemetery years ago, attackers desecrated the
synagogues with Nazi slogans and painted swastikas on their
facade.
</P>
<P>
This incident is not an isolated one: anti-Semitic incidents
have taken place recently in the Netherlands, Italy, Switzerland,
Portugal, Germany, and Belgium, while Denmark will see a big
neo-Nazi rally in Roskilde Saturday and the extreme-right in
Norway are winning unprecedented support in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
Unknown people placed leaflets denying the existence of Nazi
death chambers on cars parked near an open-air film theater Monday
evening near Zurich, Switzerland, when the movie "The List of
Schindler" was being shown.
</P>
<P>
The military aide of former Portuguese President Mario Soares
and candidate for the mayorship of Porto, General Azeredo,
described in a published article the Jewish nation as "the
inventor of usury which made it odious and persecuted by many
peoples in the course of history."
</P>
<P>
In the two Dutch cities of Alphen aan den Rijn and Woubruge,
unknown people distributed Wednesday and today on parked cars
leaflets printed with the pictures of Hess and accusing the
British government of murdering the former Nazi leader, who
committed suicide on August 17, 1987, in the prison of
Berlin-Spandau in West Berlin.
</P>
<P>
People protested in the German city of Hamburg today when an
exhibition of the works of Nazi movie shooter Leni Riefenstahl,
who produced numerous big propaganda films for Hitler, was opened
in an art gallery.
</P>
<P>
In the Italian capital Rome, a mysterious group called itself
"Beam of Revolutionary Action -- Core Alessandro Pavolini,"
which is named after an Italian wartime fascist leader, Wednesday
asked for the "symbolic hanging" of paper effigies bearing the
names of the Italian partisans who killed 33 German SS soldiers in
an ambush in central Rome on March 23, 1944.
</P>
<P>
In the Belgian city of Antwerp, where lives a big Jewish
community specialized in diamond-cutting, the extreme-right party
Vlaam Blok has been campaigning for the naming of a street after a
wartime Flemish SS officer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
