<HEADLINE> US Consumer Prices Up 0.2 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Consumer prices in the U.S.
increased by a modest 0.2 percent in July, the U.S. Labor
Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the increase in its Consumer Price
Index was also the largest since a 0.3 percent advance last
February. Increases in each of the following four months were just
0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The gain in July resulted in an increase of 1.5 percent annual
rate in the index so far this year comparing with an inflation
rate of 3.3 percent for all of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The July increase in consumer prices was held back by a 0.1
percent dip in energy costs. It was the fifth straight month that
energy prices failed to rise. Food prices climbed 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The so-called core inflation rate -- excluding the volatile
food and energy costs -- also rose 0.2 percent, up slightly from a
0.1 percent gain in June. That translated into a 2.4 percent
annual rate of increase so far this year compared with 2.6 percent
in 1996..
</P>
<P>
Although inflation remains contained, many analysts fear it
could ignite from rapid economic growth and prompt the U.S.
Federal Reserve (Fed) to raise short-term interest rates later
this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed policy-makers will meet again next week and most
analysts don't expect a rate increase in this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
