<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oklahoma Bombing Defendant Sentenced to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. District Judge Richard
Matsch today formally sentenced Oklahoma City bomber Timothy
McVeigh to death for the truck bomb attack on the Murrah federal
building that killed 168 people in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Imposing the death sentence returned by jurors in Denver,
Colorado, on June 13, Matsch said, "It is the judgment of the
court that Timothy McVeigh be sentenced to death on all 11
counts," according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
Matsch then told McVeigh that he would be put to death by
injection. McVeigh is the 13th man on the federal death row.
</P>
<P>
Matsch then asked McVeigh, "Do you have any questions?" McVeigh
responded, "Not with this court, your honor."
</P>
<P>
McVeigh's lead attorney Stephen Jones has 10 days from
McVeigh's formal sentencing to file an appeal with the 10th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver. He told reporters after the
sentencing that he had filed a notice of appeal.
</P>
<P>
In an interview this week with a Buffalo, New York, newspaper,
McVeigh said he wants Jones removed from the case, accusing the
attorney of lying to him.
</P>
<P>
McVeigh, 29, was convicted on June 2 of eight counts of
first-degree murder in the deaths of federal officers in the
building when he blew it up, and three bombing charges.
</P>
<P>
His alleged accomplice Terry Nichols, charged identically, is
scheduled to go to trial on September 29. Nichols has asked for a
change of venue, suggesting San Francisco as an alternative to
Denver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
