<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ex-Fighters Protest Suspension of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's former freedom
fighters will continue to press for their demand for pension
cumulation payments until the government meets its obligations
to them, war veterans leader Chenjerayi Hunzvi said today.
</P>
<P>
Chenjerayi Hunzvi said that arrests, detentions, blackmail and
mudslinging will not abate the situation which has recently seen
hundreds of ex-combatants picketing the ruling Zimbabwe African
National Union (PF) and government offices, including the
presidential residence, demanding an immediate disbursement of
disability pensions.
</P>
<P>
''The ex-combatants are very much disgruntled because they are
living a destitute life and you cannot give excuses that they
must be loyal," said Hunzvi, Chairman of the Zimbabwe National
Liberation War Veterans Association.
</P>
<P>
" The best way to solve this is to understand and appreciate
their plight by meeting the demands of the war veterans,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that arrests would only provoke resentment.
</P>
<P>
''It will be very stupid of someone to arrest an ex-combatant
and think it will solve anything. The war veterans have been
quiet for too long so people must think why are they uprising
now,'' Hunzvi said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, about hundred ex-combatants protesting the
suspension of pension cumulation payments, ransacked the ruling
ZANU (PF) national headquarters in Harare, cuting telephone lines
and looting foods. They went on their demonstrations today,
demanding to meet President Robert Mugabe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
