<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Suspends Afghan Embassy Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States decided
to suspend operations at the Afghanistan embassy in Washington
because of its factional contention over who would be the
representative of the fighting country, State Department said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The (State) Department has been forced to take this action
because of continuing contention among Afghan factions within
the embassy over who represents Afghanistan and our belief that
there is no effective government in the country," State
Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The "temporary" suspension will come effective on August
21st, but "the suspension does not signify a break in relations
nor any diminution of U.S. government interest in promoting a
peace process in Afghanistan," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
There are two diplomats in the Afghan embassy, both of whom
claimed to represent their country. One is Seraj Jamal,
nominated charge d'affaires by the Taliban, and the other is Yar
Mohammad Mohabbat, who was appointed as charge d'affaires by the
old government.
</P>
<P>
In May, the Taliban asked Mahabbat to give up his post in
favor of Jamal but the U.S. State Department had not accredited
Jamal as his successor, one source disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Rubin hoped the decision made by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright to suspend the Afghan embassy's operation would
encourage the factions in Afghanistan to end the fighting and
form a broadly based representative government.
</P>
<P>
While the Afghan embassy in Washington was ordered to stop
working, the Afghan consulate in New York will remain open
"because the consulate provides useful services to the Afghan
American community, Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
