<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, August 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar and Thailand today officially inaugurated a
friendship bridge on the Moei (Thaungyin River linking Myanmar's
Myawaddy and Thailand's Maesot.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the bridge, which was jointly built by Myanmar
and Thailand, is expected to facilitate trade, transport and
communications between the two countries, adding a link in the
Asian highway construction plan
project. (BC-Myanmar-Thailand-Border Bridge)
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Georgia and Abkhazia agreed today to put an end to
their conflict through peaceful means, an Itar-Tass news agency
report said from the Georgian capital of Tibilisi.
</P>
<P>
Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze and Vladislav Ardzinba,
leader of the Abkhazia republic in Georgia, signed a statement in
Tibilisi and pledged not to let bloodshed happen
again. (BC-Georgia-Abkhazia-Peace)
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Thai government announced today a cabinet
reshuffle, which has been approved by King Bhumibol Adulyadej.
</P>
<P>
Two newcomers, former deputy prime minister Thaksin Shinawatra
and former finance minister Virabhongse Ramangura, both non-MPs,
joined the cabinet as deputy prime ministers. (BC-Thailand-Cabinet
Reshuffle)
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU -- Heavy fighting reportedly broke out Thursday in
Somalia's southwestern region of Bakol between the militiamen of
Hussein Mohamed Aidid and those of the Rehanwein Resistance Army
(RRA).
</P>
<P>
At least 30 people were killed and about a dozen others were
wounded during fierce clashes at Dhiil village, 32 km north of
Huddor town. (BC-Somalia-heavy fighting)
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Hong Kong's economy maintained sustained growth in
the first half of 1997 thanks to strong domestic demand and close
ties with the Chinese inland areas, today's Ta Kung Pao quoted
Tsang Hin Chi, chairman of the Chinese General Chamber of
Commerce, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's foreign trade kept steady growth in the first six
months, with total exports up 3.2 percent and total imports up 4.6
percent in value compared with the same period of 1996, said the
business leader. (BC-Hong Kong-Economy)
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto did not
visit the controversial Yasukuni Shrine today, the 52nd
anniversary of Japan's surrender in World War II.
</P>
<P>
The shrine, which houses the memorial tablets of 14 class-A war
criminals including Japan's wartime prime minister Hideki Tojo and
other Japanese military personnel, is a symbol of militarism in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's visit to the shrine last year attracted severe
criticism from Japan's neighboring countries, which forced him to
announce that he would not visit the shrine any more while in
office. (BC-Japan-Hashimoto-Shrine)
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Political parties in Japan issued statements today to
mark the 52nd anniversary of Japan's defeat in World War II, Kyodo
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) said Japan must
repent the past and strive continuously to strengthen friendly,
forward-looking ties with Asia-Pacific countries.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democratic Party (SDP) said Japan must deeply repent
the fact that its war of aggression and colonial rule led to the
suffering to people in neighboring Asian countries. (BC-Japan-War
Anniversary)
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese leaders expressed "deep remorse" for Japan's
role in World War II at a ceremony held here today to mark the
52nd anniversary of Japan's surrender.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto reiterated
"deep remorse" for Japan's wartime acts and expressed condolences
to war victims, particularly those in neighboring Asian
nations. (BC-Japan-Surrender-Memorial) 
</P>
</TEXT>
