<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Meets With Senior US Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen told a senior US diplomat here today that
more co-operation between China and the US in the United Nations
affairs will not only benefit bilateral relations but will also
serve peace, security and development in the Asia-Pacific region
and in the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The remark came in a meeting with the US's Permanent
Representative to the UN Bill Richardson, where Qian said that, as
two permanent members of the UN Security Council, China and the US
have major responsibilities for maintaining international peace
and security and play a very important role in the UN.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the two have identical or similar interests in
many areas, though there are differences, and that the Chinese
side is ready to increase consultation and co-operation with the
US in the UN in every aspect, especially in UN Security Council
work.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said that the two countries have had sound
co-operation in the UN Security Council and in other areas and
that he hopes that the two sides will further their co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhaoxing, Chinese vice-foreign minister, and William
McCahill, charge d'affaires ad interim of the US Embassy in
Beijing, attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Li also held discussions with Richardson today on reforms in
the Security Council and on UN fiscal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Li called reforming the Security Council a profound matter and
said that it is imperative that full and careful discussions be
held and that an attempt be made to reach an agreement. This
reform can not be done at a moment's notice, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In reforming the UN Security Council, he said, China agrees to
necessary and suitable reforms and that any expansion of the
council should comply with a principle of equitable geographical
distribution of member states. Developing countries, he said,
account for more than two-thirds of the member states, so any
expansion should reflect their desires and also take their
interests into consideration.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that China is still a developing country and
that its per capita GNP is relatively low, but that the country
has tried its best to contribute to the UN.
</P>
<P>
The UN's financial issues, he said, are something China is
concerned and worried about, especially a financial crisis in the
long run. "Timely and complete payment of UN dues is the
obligation of every UN member, according to the UN Charter," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Richardson arrived here earlier today for consultations with
his Chinese counterpart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
