<HEADLINE> Tajik Government Troops, Rebels Fight Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Fighting renewed today between
government troops and rebel forces in western Tajikistan despite a
peace agreement hammered out this week.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass agency quoted the rebel leader, Colonel Makhmud
Khudoiberdyev, as saying fighting flared because pro-government
troops and heavy artillery did not withdraw from positions outside
Kurgan-Tyube, 110 kilometers south of the Tajik capital of
Dushanbe.
</P>
<P>
The rebel brigade's commander accused the government of
President Imomali Rakhmonov of not fulfilling its part of the
peace agreement struck on Wednesday. He warned that the government
would face a "new spiral of the armed stand-off with unpredictable
consequences" if its troops did not withdraw immediately.
</P>
<P>
Khudoiberdyev, a motorized rifle brigade commander, was
dismissed from his post by Tajik President Imomali Rakhmonov on
Wednesday for leading the brigade mutiny. He is believed to be
the most powerful military leader in the remote central Asian
country.
</P>
<P>
Fighting erupted between the brigade and government troops last
weekend just weeks after Rakhmonov signed a peace agreement with
Islamic opposition guerrillas which ended four years of civil
war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
