<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Confirmed as World's Oldest Person </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A 116-year-old Canadian woman has
been recognized as the world's oldest living human being, said
reports today.
</P>
<P>
The Guinness Book of World Records announced Thursday that Mrs.
Marie-Louise Meilleur, who was born on August 29, 1880 in Quebec,
Canada, is the oldest person in the world.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Meilleur inherited the title left vacant by the death 11
days ago of 122-year-old French woman Jeanne Calment.
</P>
<P>
Though there are other claimants for the title, she was the
only person in the world able to provide documents such as a birth
certificate, marriage licenses and census records.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Meilleur is now living in a nursing home in Corbeil, near
North Bay, Ontario, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
She has outlived two husbands and eight children. She has 75
grandchildren, 80 great-grandchildren and 55 great-great-children.
</P>
<P>
Her descendants said that throughout her life, she was an
energetic woman who smoked until she was in her 90s.
</P>
<P>
She never drank alcohol, didn't eat meat. She once said the
secret to her longerity was manual work and prayers.
</P>
<P>
"She always said that hard work never kills a person. She must
be right," said Rita Meilleur, 72, the youngest of her 10
children.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Meilleur does not speak much now, for she is blind and
almost totally deaf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
