<HEADLINE> Vancouver Exchange to Stop Trading Options </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Vancouver Stock Exchange
(VSE), the third largest in Canada, will cease trading options on
August 22, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
The move represents a continuation of the exchange's return to
its roots in the venture capital securities market, the Financial
Post newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"Options are move appropriate for senior companies and not
appropriate for junior listings," a VSE spokesperson was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
From August 25, all options trading in Canada must be routed
through the Toronto Stock Exchange or the Montreal Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The VSE began trading options in 1983. It is estimated that
between 10 and 15 percent of Canada's options business goes
through the exchange.
</P>
<P>
But the market has failed to become a strong revenue generator
for the exchange.
</P>
<P>
The VSE is also rethinking its commitment to the Vancouver
International Securities Trading Access (VISTA).
</P>
<P>
Launched less than a year ago, the VISTA system allows
after-hours VSE trading in Asia and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Since the pilot project has attracted little investor interest,
the VSE said it will decide whether to continue the operation.
</P>
<P>
The latest developments are "strategic business decisions" on
the part of the new management to return the VSE to its 1907 roots
as a venture capital market, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
