<HEADLINE> DPRK, Japan Try to Restart Stalled Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) and Japan are planning preparatory talks
in the Chinese capital of Beijing next week to set a schedule for
long-stalled negotiations aimed at normalizing diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed earlier today to hold talks on August
21 at Japan's embassy in Beijing. These would set a schedule and
agenda for formal normalization talks, which had been stalled for
nearly five years over disputes between both sides, the Korean
Central News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which controlled the Korean Peninsula as a colony from
1910 to 1945, normalized relations with South Korea in 1965, but
has yet to establish diplomatic ties with the DPRK. 
</P>
