<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Summer Camp Teaches History Lesson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Japanese students
met today in Nanjing, capital city of east China's Jiangsu
Province, to attend a summer camp on "Witnesses to the Nanjing
Massacre".
</P>
<P>
Students from 14 Tokyo and Osaka middle schools will visit
survivors of the historical event, which took place 60 years ago,
with the help of local middle school students.
</P>
<P>
Japanese troops seized Nanjing, the then capital of China, in
December of 1937. Some 300,000 people were killed and thousands
of women were raped during the ensuing occupation.
</P>
<P>
"We will describe the situation of the war to our compatriots
when we are back home," said one Japanese student, "we will not
let such a tragedy happen again."
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 of Nanjing's students have been involved in the
work of looking for survivors of the Nanjing Massacre since July,
and have located 1,500 of the remaining survivors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
