<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister Meets With Vietnam Government Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen, in a meeting today with a Vietnamese
government delegation, said that settling boundary issues
between China and Viet Nam is in the fundamental interest of the
two countries and is the wish of the leaders and the peoples of
both countries.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by Vietnamese Deputy Foreign Minister Vu
Khoan, came for the fifth round of government-level boundary
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that China and Vietnam have similar national
situations and face the same task of promoting economic
development and the standard of living, and both need a long-term
stable and peaceful international environment.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the fifth round of boundry negotiation at government
level is held under the circumstances of the important consensus
reached by leaders of the two countries not long ago on speeding
up the process of negotiations, making the negotiation an
important issue.
</P>
<P>
Qian said he is convinced that, with these joint efforts,
issues remaining from the past can be settled as soon as possible,
to promote good neighborly relations for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Vu Khoan and his party arrived here Tuesday as guests of
Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, attending the fifth
round of boundry negotiations between China and Viet Name at
government level.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the two sides held talks in a friendly
and frank atmosphere and the both commented on the progress made
since the fourth round of negotiations last September.
</P>
<P>
They also exchanged extensive views on how to speed up the
progress of negotiation and reached great consensus.
</P>
<P>
Tang and Vietnamese Ambassador to China Dang Nghiem Hoanh were
present at the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
