<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Draft Charter Passes Third Reading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Ninety-two out of the 99 members
of the Constitution Drafting assembly of Thailand voted today in
favor of the new charter draft, according to local TV reports.
</P>
<P>
The draft will then be submitted for studies by
parliamentarians, who are due to vote on it next month.
</P>
<P>
The 99-member drafting assembly was elected last December and
was given 240 days to draft a new charter.
</P>
<P>
Many people pin much hopes on it, seeing it as a way to reform
and improve Thailand's politics, while others believe that the new
charter, which has as many as 336 articles, some highly
controversial, will not be a panacea to cure all political
ailments of the country.
</P>
<P>
Among the controversial articles is ban on MPs concurrently
holding Cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
A number of MPs may not like this clause, but the drafting
assembly argues that a power separation is needed to keep better
check on the state.
</P>
<P>
Under the current Constitution, the overwhelming majority of
the Cabinet are MPs, with only a few rare exceptions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
