<HEADLINE> Australia Vows to Be Regional Financial Center: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia would become the
second financial center in the Asia-Pacific region, Australian
Prime Minister John Howard said tonight in a speech signaling a
more interventionist industry policy.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to making Australia the second financial
center of the region after Tokyo for the 21st century," the prime
minister told an industry conference dinner in the coastal city of
Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and Hong Kong are currently the main financial
centers after Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
This would partly be based on Australia's advantage in the
information sector where growth information technologies were
flourishing, according to the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
"Australia ranks second only to the United States in computer
ownership and our spending on information technology as a
proportion to gross domestic product is 2.8 percent compared to
1.9 percent in Japan and 3.1 percent in the United States," Howard
said.
</P>
<P>
He promised that his government would soon announce new
incentives for the technology and telecommunication industries to
help bridge the information gap between cities and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
He stressed Australia's industry policy must be forward looking
in an era of globalization.
</P>
<P>
"Our focus is on facilitating adjustment from declining to
emerging activities, encouraging international best practice and
gaining access to lucrative markets, particularly in the
Asia-Pacific region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The high unemployment rate of 8.7 percent and slow economic
growth have been widely considered major problems for the prime
minister to win the next election as his government has less than
two years to make preparations.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the government is considering wide-ranging
industry policy adjustments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
