<HEADLINE> Iceland President Seeks Close Ties With Finland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Iceland President Olafur
Grimsson, soon to leave on a visit to Finland, said his country
has a strong desire to strengthen cooperation with Finland.
</P>
<P>
Grimsson's remarks were reported today in an interview with the
Finnish newspaper, Helsingin Sanomat.
</P>
<P>
He said status of Finland, as member state of the European
Union, and Iceland as member state of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), provided the two countries with the
possibility of exerting future influence over European security
and political cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Grimsson said that when NATO was playing an increasing bigger
role in Europe, it was very important for Iceland and Finland to
strengthen cooperation in security and politics.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that Iceland had a tradition of
strong contacts with Baltic countries, and that following his
visits to north European countries, he would pay state visits to
Baltic countries.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Iceland's stand for not joining the European
Union, pointing out that Iceland was not willing to put its
fishing zones under the control of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Grimsson will pay a state visit to Finland from August 25 to
28. 
</P>
