<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia, Abkhazia Determine to End Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Georgia and Abkhazia agreed today
to put an end to their conflict through peaceful means, an
Itar-Tass news agency report said from the Georgian capital of
Tibilisi.
</P>
<P>
Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze and Vladislav Ardzinba,
leader of the Abkhazia republic in Georgia, signed a statement in
Tibilisi and pledged not to let bloodshed happen again.
</P>
<P>
The report said that at the presence of Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Shevardnadze and Ardzinba on Thursday
held several hours of talks and discussed means to settle the
Abkhazia conflict.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the two sides should exercise tolerance
towards each other and take the stand of reconciliation and
compromise.
</P>
<P>
They pledged not to resort to force to settle the existing
conflict and, under no circumstances, should they let bloodshed
happen again.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to maintain regular contacts in order to
resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
Ardzinba and Primakov arrived in Tibilisi together on
Thursday. Russia had been making efforts to mediate between
Georgia and its breakaway Republic of Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin said on August 1 that he
planned to invite the leaders of Georgia and Abkhazia to go to
Moscow for talks, in order to sign an accord with them to ensure
peace and territorial integrity in this region.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Abkhazia declared independence from Georgia in
July 1992, and the Georgian government sent troops into this
autonomous republic in the following month, which led to armed
conflicts between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Under the mediation of the United Nations and Russia, the two
sides signed a ceasefire accord in May 1994, and a Russian
peace-keeping force entered and stationed itself in the conflict
area in May 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, the final status of the Republic of Abkhazia remains
unsettled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
