<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loan Helps Children's Health In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
province plans to vaccinate 90 percent of its people by the year
2000 with the aid of a 7.5 million US dollars World Bank loan.
</P>
<P>
The health care improvement loan is being provided over a
five-year period beginning in 1996, while provincial health
authorities will raise supporting funds of 38.48 million yuan
(US$4.64 million).
</P>
<P>
The project will greatly improve vaccination in the province,
said a provincial health official. The money will be used for more
than 48,000 units of vaccine storage equipment and instruments and
to train 17,400 workers.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-three poverty-stricken counties in the province will
get priority in the treatments and impoverished families will get
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
The project's goals include: an infant-mortality rate from
tetanus among infants of less than one per thousand; decreasing
the incidence and mortality rate of measles from the 1982 rate by
90 percent and 95 percent respectively; and lowering the incidence
rate of pertussis and diphtheria to less than one per 100,000 and
0.005 per 100,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
