<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Official on Legislative Council Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) said today
that a government-drafted bill on the overall arrangements for the
first SAR Legislative Council elections due to take place in late
May next year would be tabled before the Provisional Legislative
Council next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the document entitled the Legislative Council Bill
at a news conference this afternoon, Secretary for Electoral
Affairs Michael Suen Ming-yeung stressed that a major voter
registration will be mounting between December and January and the
Election Committee must be established in early April.
</P>
<P>
"Having carefully considered the views of the community, we
have completed drafting of the relevant electoral legislation,"
Suen said. "It will be introduced into the Provisional Legislative
Council on August 20 for the first and second readings."
</P>
<P>
The bill will provide a legal basis for the overall
arrangements for the Legislative Council election, and for matters
such as the delineation of the electorate of the functional
constituencies and the Election Committee, he explained.
</P>
<P>
"The clear and consistent objective of the SAR government is to
ensure that elections take place on an open, fair and honest
basis, so that all candidates could compete in a level playing
field," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, the Legislative Council of the Hong Kong
SAR shall be composed of 60 members, with 30 to be returned by 30
functional constituencies, 10 by the Election Committee and 20 by
five geographical constituencies through direct elections
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The division of geographical constituencies and the voting
method for direct elections therein, the delimitation of
functional sectors and corporate bodies, their seat allocation and
election methods, and the method for electing members of the
Legislative Council shall be specified by an electoral law
introduced by the SAR government and passed by the PLC.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon the delineation of the functional constituency
electorate, Suen said: "We have adopted the traditional concept
and standards. This approach is to ensure that various functional
constituencies are representative and of importance, so that the
future legislative body could reflect different views of the
community."
</P>
<P>
As to the formation of the Election Committee, he said that the
great majority of the 800 members making up the electoral body
will be chosen through election from within the relevant
sub-sectors. The Electoral Affairs Commission, which will soon be
established, will supervise the electoral process to ensure
openness and fairness, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need to complete a number of key steps as
soon as possible, adding: "This means that the progress of each
key step would have a direct impact on that of the other."
</P>
<P>
"For example, the Electoral Affairs Commission cannot take
formal steps to draw up recommendations on geographical boundaries
 until the number of geographical constituencies is determined,"
he said. "There is no certainty on the latter, however, until the
 Legislative Council Bill is passed."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
