<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Stage Largest Timepiece Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- More than 760 timepiece
companies from 17 countries and regions will be in Hong Kong next
month for the 16th Hong Kong Watch &AMP; Clock Fair, making it the
world's largest timepiece trade fair in terms of number of
exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing here today, Co-chairman of the
Fair Organizing Committee Stanley Lau said that Hong Kong's watch
and clock industry has conducted business as usual after Hong
Kong's return to its motherland.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Hong Kong remains a leading trader of watches, clocks
and timepiece components. Last year, Hong Kong exported 47.9
billion HK dollar (6.18 billion U.S. dollar) worth timepieces, up
two percent over 1995."
</P>
<P>
"Our fastest-growing markets are in the increasingly affluent
regions of Asia and Latin America," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In the five months of 1997, Hong Kong's timepiece exports rose
49 percent to the Philippines, 29 percent to Paraguay and 25
percent to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
According to Lau, the 16th annual edition of the fair will
feature more than 760 exhibitors, up from 713 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The five-day fair will feature group pavilions from France,
Germany, Italy, South Korea and China, and individual exhibitors
from Denmark, India, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Singapore, Spain,
Switzerland, Thailand and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Last year's Hong Kong Watch &AMP; Clock Fair attracted 16,000
buyers from 89 countries and regions, generating orders worth 2.4
billion HK dollars (309.67 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
