<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Casualties Rise in Cairo Shop Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The number of those injured rose
to more than 280 in the fire that ravaged a crowded shopping mall
Thursday night, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The death toll remains at three, two of the dead have been
identified, according to an Interior Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
The injured, most of them suffering from suffocation due to
inhaling smoke caused by the fire, were rushed for treatment. Up
to 252 of the injured are still in hospital.
</P>
<P>
When the fire broke out, the seven-story Al-Horreya Mall in the
plush Cairo suburb of Helioplis was still full of late-night
shoppers and merry-makers who came to enjoy a cool summer time.
</P>
<P>
The blaze was contained in two hours, but red smoke billowing
from the building had already lit up the dark sky above.
</P>
<P>
The fire destroyed 25 boutiques and two cinemas which were
still operating at that hour.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations into the cause of the fire show that
the building lacks all emergency preparations including emergency
stairs and has no emergency ventilation systems or exits.
</P>
<P>
Those who happened to be at the building during the fire had
to smash the building's windows to allow fresh air in, especially
after its central air conditioning stopped functioning. Panicked,
some jumped out of the window for life.
</P>
<P>
The first of fire engines arrived 30 minutes after the start of
the fire because of the difficulty to drive through the
overcrowded streets all around the mall.
</P>
<P>
Reports are still contradictory about the cause of the fire and
the place where it started.
</P>
<P>
Some say the fire started in either the second or fourth floor
while some survivors said that it erupted in the sixth
floor. Other survivors said that the fire ensued from a short
circuit at an elevator under repair at the mall.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses heard a deafening sound of a crack before the
outbreak of the fire and agreed that the power failure left the
entire building in darkness.
</P>
<P>
At hand at the scene to supervise firefighting operations were
Health Minister Ismail Sallam and governor of Cairo Abdel Rehim
Shehata. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Broke out in Southwest Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting reportedly
broke out Thursday in Somalia's southwestern region of Bakol
between the militiamen of Hussein Mohamed Aidid and those of the
Rehanwein Resistance Army (RRA).
</P>
<P>
At least 30 people were killed and about a dozen others were
wounded during fierce clashes at Dhiil village, 32 km north of
Huddor town.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, nine battle wagons belonging to
Hussein Aidid's faction and a hundred infantry militiamen were
involved in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
VHF radio reports received in Huddor town said the battle
wagons left the town to Dhiil village following an armed
insurgency by the RRA men in the area.
</P>
<P>
Reports added that Hussein Aidid's army contingent were
ambushed just outside the village as the infantry militiamen left
their battle wagons to search for the RRA guerrilla fighters in
the mountain lands north of the village.
</P>
<P>
Five of Hussein Aidid's battle wagons were destroyed by the
RRA infantry men using rocket-propelled grenades, hand grenades
and assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
Radio North Mogadishu supporting Ali Mahdi Mohamed quoted a
RRA spokesman Mohamed Ali Aden (Qalinle) as saying all of the 30
war victims who died on the spot were Hussein Aidid's men.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle, who is among the RRA political leaders based in north
Mogadishu told Xinhua that two of his fighters were killed and
five others wounded.
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that his forces have confiscated six BKM guns,
seven RPGs and 15 assault rifles from Hussein Aidid's men during
the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid's men have perpetrated the attack and raided
their RRA militia base in Dhiil village, Qalinle added.
</P>
<P>
South Mogadishu Radio of Hussein Aidid did not mention the
fighting and none of his top lieutenants were available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
The clash is characterized as the most catastrophic since the
RRA militiamen started their hit-and-run guerrilla fighting
against Hussein Aidi's men in Bakol region three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, there has been no independent source to confirm
the situation in Dhiil village today and the damage caused by the
fighting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Arrested for Sending Letter Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A man who suspected of sending
a letter bomb to Sweden's justice minister was arrested thursday
by Security police, according to local reports on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The man, 23, was identified as a leader of the Aryan
Brotherhood organization.
</P>
<P>
The bomb, sent to Justice Minister Laila Freivalds in March,
was detected at a post office before being delivered. It contained
explosives and a detonator, but was not rigged to explode.
</P>
<P>
The letter demanded that two members of the Aryan Brotherhood
be released from prison and said a live bomb would be sent if they
were not.
</P>
<P>
Deputy chief prosecutor Eva Finne, speaking to the Swedish news
agency TT, denied a report in the newspaper Expressen that the man
was also suspected in a firebombing at the home of a top advocate
of Stockholm's bid for the 2004 Olympics.  
</P>
