<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Keen on Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Sichuan Province, southwest
China, expects to reap yet another good grain harvest this year
following the record 1996 grain output of slightly over 47 million
tons, or nearly a tenth of the national total.
</P>
<P>
Bumper harvests have enabled the province to contribute greatly
to the reform and opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan has placed top priority on agricultural development
since 1992. Related efforts have enabled the rural economy to
reach a new high, with last year's per capita income for farmers
reaching 1,453 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan also paid special attention to applying science and
technology in agriculture. The province has led China in seed
breeding research for the past five years, with scientific and
technological contributions reaching 50 percent in cultivated
areas.
</P>
<P>
The province sends more than 20,000 agriculturists to rural
areas annually to promote the application of new technology.
</P>
<P>
The province's livestock industry has led the nation for 20
consecutive years in output and sales volume for pigs.
</P>
<P>
Over five million Sichuan natives working as migrant laborers,
the largest number from any province, return earnings of 20
billion yuan to their home province annually. The over 300,000
former migrant workers who have returned to open businesses have
emerged as a major force boosting local economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan's township enterprises, which employ over 10 million
redundant rural workers, are in transition from cottage industry
to highly efficient technology-intensive enterprise groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
