<HEADLINE> Sino-Australian Stress on Human Rights Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- An Australian delegation, led by
Bill Farmer, deputy secretary of the Department of Foreign Affairs
and Trade of Australia, visited China between August 11-14 at the
invitation of Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Li Zhaoxing.
</P>
<P>
Li and other high-ranking officials with China's Foreign
Ministry held talks with the delegation, which also met with
officials, advisers and scholars from relevant Chinese departments
and organizations.
</P>
<P>
Both sides participated in four days of "open and productive"
talks concerning their respective approaches and concerns related
to a broad range of human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from both governments reiterated the importance
of the principle of the universality and indivisibility of human
rights and recognizing that respect of human rights is an integral
part of sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
They acknowledged the existence of different perspectives and
approaches to human rights.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that equal and constructive talks, dialogue and
cooperation between countries is important to promoting and
protecting human rights.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to examine proposals for practical
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Officials from both countries will continue to work on
developing technical cooperation programs in relevant fields. The
Australian side intends to provide 300,000 Australian dollars for
the program during this financial year, and both parties agreed to
engage in dialogue on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Australian delegation included officials from
the Dept. of Foreign Affairs and Trade, the Office of the
Attorney-General and the Australian Agency for International
Development.
</P>
<P>
Relevant Chinese departments and organizations exchanging views
with the Australian delegation included the Legislative Affairs
Commission of the National People's Congress Standing Committee,
the Supreme People's Court, the Supreme People's Procuratorate,
the State Nationalities Affairs Commission, the Ministry of
Justice, the Bureau of Religious Affairs, the All-China Women's
Federation, and the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The delegation's visit followed Australian Prime Minister John
Howard's visit to China and Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji's
Australian tour earlier this year, as well as an April visit by
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
