<HEADLINE> Egyptian Food Shipments Allowed into Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israel has agreed to allow
shipments of Egyptian food, medicine and powder milk to cross to
the Palestinian self-rule areas, the Middle East News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Palestinian Liaison Committee was quoted as
saying that shipments of Egyptian rice and flour have already been
given access to the Palestinian areas through Rafah checkpoint on
the Egyptian-Israeli border, which was closed early this month.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 Palestinians working in the Gulf countries were
also allowed to travel to the Egyptian Al Arish Airport from Gaza
Strip today together with their families to fly back to their work
after a summer break at home.
</P>
<P>
These measures came as results of international efforts to ease
the siege, among other Israeli security measures, imposed on the
Palestinians since two suicide bombs killed 14 Israeli civilians
in Jerusalem on July 30.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority warned that conditions could
explode at any minute as its reserves of food and medicines are
almost exhausted. Palestinian losses due to the closure were
estimated at several million U.S. dollars daily.
</P>
<P>
Israel has ordered the closure of the crossing points along its
border with Egypt since the bombing attacks, leading to a halt in
the traffic of Egyptian commodities on the trade route into Israel
and the Palestinian autonomy areas. Only foreign tourists were
allowed to pass.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians, left out in the cold for the third week in front
of the Rafah checkpoint awaiting to get into the Gaza Strip, have
been complaining that they are running short of money.
</P>
<P>
Israel Thursday lifted a travel ban that had barred
Palestinians from traveling out of two major cities in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
But the easing of travel restrictions on the cities of Ramallah
and Hebron did not affect the closure which prevents tens of
thousands of Palestinians from entering Israel.
</P>
<P>
The move followed a four-day misson by U.S. Mideast envoy
Dennis Ross, who had urged Israel to eliminate any measures which
prevent tens of thousands of Palestinians from entering Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
