<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Approves Integrated Anti-Drug Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today approved in principle an integrated strategy to combat the
serious drug problem in the country.
</P>
<P>
The strategy calls for the full cooperation and proper
coordination among the five pillars of the country's criminal
justice system, namely, law enforcement, courts, prosecution,
correctional institutions and the community.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos said earlier that a sixth pillar, international
cooperation, is also needed for the success of the all-out war
against drug lords and drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
According to the strategy, the government and the citizenry
will cooperate in conducting information drives against dangerous
drugs in schools, communities, labor circles and villages down to
the street level.
</P>
<P>
They would also take all legal and unrelenting actions to
prevent the communities against dangerous drugs through
cooperative efforts, conduct investigation, arrest and prosecution
to control the sources of illegal drugs and apply the full force
of the law against drug lords, drug traffickers, drug pushers and
scalawags in the police.
</P>
<P>
The government and the citizenry would also conduct research
and studies to support legislative proposals and other measures to
amend outdated laws dealing with dangerous drugs and establish
more rehabilitation and treatment centers for victims of dangerous
drugs.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Ramos ordered the immediate release of 50
million pesos (1.7 million U.S. dollars) as initial funding for
the success of the strategy.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Philippines had at least 1.7 million
drug addicts and that illegal drug sales reached 9.5 billion U.S.
dollars a year in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
