<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Severs Relations with Chad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- China has severed diplomatic
relations with Chad, a north African country which on Tuesday
announced that it would resume "diplomatic relations" with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang announced
that the government of the People's Republic of China decided to
sever diplomatic relations with Chad on August 15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to Shen, "The implementation of all the agreements
between the two governments will cease immediately."
</P>
<P>
"The government of Chad must bear full responsibility for
all consequences arising from its erroneous decision," said Shen.
</P>
<P>
The government of Chad and Taiwan authorities jointly announced
the restoration of so-called "diplomatic relations" on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Shen, "The decision of the government of Chad
violates the principles set forth in the communique announcing the
establishment of diplomatic relations between China and Chad
on November 28, 1972.
</P>
<P>
"The decision also violates Chad's commitment that 'the
Government of the People's Republic of China is the sole legal
government representing all Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"The erroneous decision of the government of Chad has seriously
damaged China's sovereignty, has sabotaged friendly relations and
cooperation between the two countries, and runs counter to the
fundamental interests and wishes of the two peoples."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Chinese government has provided selfless
assistance to Chad for many years and has made positive
contributions to Chad's economic construction and social
development.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the people of the two countries enjoy a
traditional friendship, and that the Chinese government does not
wish to see a reversal in Sino-Chad relations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to Chad Gao Ruming issued a stern
representation to the government of Chad today in Chad's capital
of N'Djamena concerning Chad's resumption of "diplomatic
relations" with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Gao also conveyed the Chinese government's strong protest on
the issue to the government of Chad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
