<HEADLINE> Commissioner's Office on Hong Kong Fishing Boat Detained by Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the
Commissioner's Office of the Chinese Foreign Ministry in Hong Kong
said here today that the office has been working to help settle
the fishing boat issue, in which 23 Chinese fishermen, including
three Hong Kong residents, were detained by the Philippines late
last month.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong boat was caught by the Philippine military on
July 31, 1997, when it scurried for safety near Half Moon Shoal
against typhoon Victor on its way to the Indonesian waters,
according to the Commissioner's Office. The boat was later handed
to concerned departments in Palawan, the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Wu Hongbo, the spokesman, said today that the Chinese embassy
has negotiated with the Philippines on the matter and urged Manila
to release the boat and the crew with the least delay. The embassy
has sent consul officials to visit the detained fishermen and
provided them with consul services and protection.
</P>
<P>
There were 23 fishermen on the boat, including three residents
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR). The other 20
were from Taishan in South China's Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that since the fishing boat was seized by the
Philippines, the Commissioner's Office has kept close contact with
the Chinese embassy in Manila and informed the SAR government of
the latest progress, so as to help solve the problem as soon as
possible.  
</P>
</TEXT>
