<HEADLINE> China Impact Boosts Hong Kong Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's economy maintained
sustained growth in the first half of 1997 thanks to strong
domestic demand and close ties with the Chinese inland areas,
today's Ta Kung Pao quoted Tsang Hin Chi, chairman of the Chinese
General Chamber of Commerce, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's foreign trade kept steady growth in the first six
months, with total exports up 3.2 percent and total imports up 4.6
percent in value compared with the same period of 1996, said the
business leader.
</P>
<P>
Transactions were brisk on stock and property market in the
first half of this year, and retail business continued to pick up,
according to Tsang.
</P>
<P>
With a total market capitalization of 548 billion US dollars,
Hong Kong emerged as the sixth largest stock exchange in the
globe. Its benchmark index, the Hang Seng Index, hit historic
highs time and again during the January-June period.
</P>
<P>
Tsang contributed the sustained economic growth in Hong Kong to
a fundamental element -- China impact. The Chinese inland areas
has become Hong Kong's largest export market, taking in 35 percent
of the city's total export.
</P>
<P>
Inexpensive labor and low rents in China's inland areas helped
Hong Kong manufacturers reduce production costs and enhance
competitiveness of their products, said Tsang.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the GDP growth in Hong Kong would reach 5.4
percent in the year of 1997, up from the growth rate of 4.7
percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
