<HEADLINE> Experts Discuss Safe Use of Chemicals in Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Experts representing
governments, employer and labor organization in southern Africa
are meeting in Swaziland today to work out a draft code on the
safe use of chemicals in the region.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting will formulate a common principle on the
safe handling and use of chemicals in member states of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC), reports reaching
here from Mbabane said.
</P>
<P>
Philomene Makolo, an official of the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), told the delegates that more than
80,000 chemicals are now in use worldwide.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, there is little information and knowledge on
proper handling of chemicals in all SADC member states.
</P>
<P>
The SADC was formed five years ago to coordinate efforts for a
common market. The regional grouping is made up of 12 countries,
with a total population of 150 million and a combined gross
domestic product of 170 billion U. S. Dollars. 
</P>
