<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Compulsory Conscription Becomes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- S. Africa has announced
that its newly established National Defense Force will not
recruit forcibly the military personnel who served in the
apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
Local press today quoted Deputy Defense Minister Ronnie
Kasrils as saying that apartheid-era soldiers can, however,
volunteer for service. If they do, they will be obliged to make
themselves available for call-ups.
</P>
<P>
Kasrils said that volunteers would be contractually obliged to
make themselves available for call-ups, possibly for up to 16
years. About 500,000 men at the ages of from 22 to 55 are
affected.
</P>
<P>
However, as the commander-in-chief of the defense force, the
president of S. Africa will have the authority to reintroduce
conscription.
</P>
<P>
S. Africa's current conscription was originally introduced in
1953 as a selective ballot system, and became compulsory in 1968.
It was originally for nine months but later became two years and
then reduced to one year.
</P>
<P>
The conscription was officially suspended in 1994, which saw
the first non-racial general elections in S. Africa, but the
status of the apartheid era conscripts has not been clarified
until now.
</P>
<P>
The conscription remained in S. Africa's statute books because
the relevant defense act was never repealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Loses 5 Bn Drs From Resources Degradation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will suffer an annual
loss of some 5.1 billion U.S. Dollars if its environmental
problems are left unsolved, accounting for 4.3 percent of its
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
According to Director-General of the federal Environmental
Protection Agency (FEPA) Adegoke Adegoroye, the figure comes from
a World Bank assessment of the Nigerian past and present inaction
to check the nation's degradation of natural resources.
</P>
<P>
At a recent national conference on sustainable development in
the capital Abuja, he said the environmental problems confronting
the country were deforestation, erosion and urban decay.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the federal government should always be protective
on the nation's natural resources, said Adegoroye who has just
concluded an assessment tour of several coastal states.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to enforce some of the related decrees
to protect forest resources and endangered species of animals.
</P>
<P>
"Reckless logging in the forest has opened the soil to
devastation of erosion," he said.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that FEPA would work with the federal department
of forestry on a new strategy for sustainable management of the
nation's forest.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Adegoroye said that sustainable development did not
mean that Nigeria must immediately shut down all polluting
industries.
</P>
<P>
To do so was to dislocate the economy, throw people out of
jobs and dislocate families as well as aggravate poverty and
social tension, he added.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that a research agenda for the country must
integrate environmental consideration at all stages of its
development for Nigeria to attain its ultimate goal of
sustainable development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Controls Hepatitis B (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved remarkable
progress in controlling Hepatitis B (HB), with more than 85
percent of infants and preschool children in urban areas having
received vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
Officials note that breakthroughs have also been recorded in
the nation's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Experts attending a recent International Symposium on Liver
Diseases pointed out that the rate of HB surface antigen (HBsAg)
seropositivity in China can be reduced to around one percent if
the HB virus (HBV) can be prevented over two generations.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that incidence rates for HB and liver cancer
caused by the virus can be reduced to very low levels.
</P>
<P>
HB is a viral infectious disease which has spread throughout
the world and is especially prevalent in China. A recent survey
showed a 58 percent HB virus infection rate in China. The
country's rate of HBsAg seropositivity is 9.75 percent, and nearly
30 million Chinese suffer from chronic HB.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that close to 80 percent of the liver cancer in
China is related with the HB.
</P>
<P>
China introduced vaccines for universal infant HB immunization
programs in Beijing and Shanghai almost a decade ago, with recent
examinations of vaccinated children showing that the rate of HBsAg
seropositivity has dropped to below one percent, down five
percentage points on levels prior to the programs.
</P>
<P>
"This indicates that the majority of children in the two cities
are protected," according to Wang Bao'en, China's authority on
liver diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Controls Hepatitis B (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Centers to manufacture HB vaccine were set up in 1984, and DNA
vaccines have since been widely used in the country's immunization
program.
</P>
<P>
China continues to give priority to infant immunization, with
programs covering children below the age of six and people working
in hospitals, schools and public places.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, China has carried out a full-scale program in
the nation's vast rural areas, while at the same time trying
to raise the vaccination rate in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
"China has manufactured amply supplies of HB vaccine to meet
needs of the immunization program," according to Prof. Wang with
the Beijing Friendship Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Wang noted that achievements have been scored in developing
anti-HBV drugs, but therapeutic effects remain less than
satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
"Prevention is still the main method for dealing with the
disease," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Experts have found that various types of traditional Chinese
medicinal herbs can effectively prevent liver fibrosis formation
and can even reverse early stages of cirrhotic change.
</P>
<P>
In addition, considerable progress has been achieved in the
research using such herbs to treat the HB virus.
</P>
<P>
Reports as early as the 1960s indicated that some herbs helped
to remove some symptoms characteristic of hepatitis
sufferers. Over the past three decades, China has carried out
clinical experiments to study the therapeutic effect herbs
offer in the treatment of liver diseases, and to develop effective
anti-HBV drugs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
