<HEADLINE> National Mourning Day Observed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The nation of Bangladesh today
paid homage to its independence leader Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur
Rahman, who was assassinated 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In the morning, President Shahabuddin Ahmed and Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina placed wreaths at the portrait of the slain leader
at the Bangabandhu memorial museum in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
All members of Bangabandhu's family, except his two daughters,
the present Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina and Sheikh Rehana, fell
victims of the pre-dawn coup led by some army officers that
drastically changed the political landscape of the country.
</P>
<P>
The August 15 putsch pushed Bangabandhu's Awami (people's)
League out of the political arena for some time, but the party,
led by Sheikh Hasina, returned to power through the national
election last year.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the Awami League was back to power, Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina's government declared August 15 as National
Mourning Day to show respect to Bangabandhu.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hasina also flied to her hometown Tungipara in northern
Gopalganj district today to attend the mourning day programs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Shahabuddin Ahmed has called for
motivating the people to materialize the dream of Bangabandhu for
building a "happy and prosperous Bangladesh".
</P>
<P>
In a message to mark the National Mourning Day, the prime
minister appealed all to make their relentless efforts for the
welfare of the unfortunate and deprived people of the country as
the "father of the nation" had done during his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
She urged all to transform this sorrow and grief into an
indomitable strength for the greater welfare of the nation to help
them march towards the challenging 21st century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
