<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Keeps Away from Controversial Shrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto did not visit the controversial Yasukuni Shrine today,
the 52nd anniversary of Japan's surrender in World War II.
</P>
<P>
The shrine, which houses the memorial tablets of 14 class-A war
criminals including Japan's wartime prime minister Hideki Tojo and
other Japanese military personnel, is a symbol of militarism in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's visit to the shrine last year attracted severe
criticism from Japan's neighboring countries, which forced him to
announce that he would not visit the shrine any more while in
office.
</P>
<P>
Following Hashimoto, Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama,
Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda and Finance Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka said that they would also not visit the shrine on August
15.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet ministers' visits to the shrine are controversial
because Japan's postwar Constitution stipulates separation of
religion and the state.
</P>
<P>
Despite all this, eight Japanese ministers including Health and
Welfare Minister Junichiro Koizumi and International Trade and
Industry Minister Shinji Sato, Transport Minister Makoto Koga and
Labor Minister Yutaka Okano visited the shrine today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Parties Mark End of World War II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Political parties in Japan issued
statements today to mark the 52nd anniversary of Japan's defeat in
World War II, Kyodo news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) said Japan must
repent the past and strive continuously to strengthen friendly,
forward-looking ties with Asia-Pacific countries.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democratic Party (SDP) said Japan must deeply repent
the fact that its war of aggression and colonial rule led to the
suffering to people in neighboring Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
"We aim to set a 'table of peace' in Asia where each country
can participate in the establishment of peace and trust," said a
statement by the SDP, a non-cabinet ally of the LDP.
</P>
<P>
Concerned about an ongoing review of the Japan-U.S. defense
cooperation guidelines, the opposition Japanese Communist Party
alleged that "the review will lead to a system whereby Japan
automatically participates in war if and when the United States
makes military intervention on the grounds of an emergency near
Japan."
</P>
<P>
"We must never allow a dangerous plan that will lead Japan once
more to a war of aggression," it said.
</P>
<P>
The largest opposition party, the New Frontier Party, said it
is determined to "establish new relations of trust with Asian and
other countries by repenting the past and making active
contributions to the international community."
</P>
<P>
New Party Sakigake said it wants to reflect deeply on how Japan
inflicted pain on its neighboring countries during World War II,
which was ended on August 15, 1945. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
