<HEADLINE> 11 Still Missing in Philippine Ship Capsize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Eleven people were still not
accounted for hours after a passenger ship carrying them sank in
the small hours this morning in the central Philippines, the
Philippine Coast Guard (PCG) said.
</P>
<P>
The number of the rescued has risen from 38 to 66, including 34
crew members and 32 passengers, Assistant Public Information
Officer for PCG Jaime Daquilanea told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Daquilanea said the death toll from the incident remained 10 as
so far only 10 bodies have been recovered. But he said the number
of the fatalities is feared to rise because of big waves and
strong winds on the sea.
</P>
<P>
Being battered by big waves and strong winds, the passenger
ship capsized and sank at 2 a.m. near Maripipi Island, Biliran
province, on its way from Cebu city to Tacloban city.
</P>
<P>
The coast guard has so far failed to determine the exact number
of passengers on the ship. According to Daquilanea, a list
provided by the ship captain showed there were 52 passengers but a
report from the owner of the ship said 88 passengers were on
board.
</P>
<P>
Two naval seacraft, two air force helicopters and some civilian
volunteers are now searching survivors at the capsize site,
Daquilanea said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
