<HEADLINE> Japanese Leaders Remorse for Victims of World War II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Japanese leaders expressed "deep
remorse" for Japan's role in World War II at a ceremony held here
today to mark the 52nd anniversary of Japan's surrender.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto reiterated
"deep remorse" for Japan's wartime acts and expressed condolences
to war victims, particularly those in neighboring Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
"The last war caused tremendous pain and sorrow not only to our
country but also to people in many countries, particularly those
in neighboring Asian nations," Hashimoto told the annual gathering.
</P>
<P>
"I am sincerely mindful of this fact and would like to offer
heartfelt condolences to them with deep remorse," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged to make an all-out effort to realize a
permanent world peace.
</P>
<P>
Emperor Akihito offered condolences to the war dead and prayed
for world peace at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"Looking back at history, I pray from the heart that the
ravages of war will never be repeated," the emperor said.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony at Nippon Budokan here was also attended by House
of Representative speaker Soichiro Ito, House of Councillors
President Juro Saito as well as other government officials and
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto today did not visit the controversial Yasukuni
Shrine, a symbol of militarism in the country.
</P>
<P>
His visit to the shrine last year attracted severe criticism
from Japan's neighboring countries and forced him to announce that
he would not visit the shrine any more while in office.
</P>
<P>
The shrine, which houses the memorial tablets of 14 class-A war
criminals including Japan's wartime prime minister Hideki Tojo and
other Japanese military personnel, is a symbol of militarism in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet ministers' visits to the shrine are controversial
because Japan's postwar Constitution stipulates separation of
religion and the state.
</P>
<P>
But eight Japanese ministers including Health and Welfare
Minister Junichiro Koizumi and International Trade and Industry
Minister Shinji Sato, Transport Minister Makoto Koga and Labor
Minister Yutaka Okano visited the shrine today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
