<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panzhihua Heavy Industrial Base Growing Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Panzhihua City in southwest
China's Sichuan Province expects its gross domestic product (GDP)
to reach 13 billion yuan by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The city is working hard to form an important part of the
economic belt along the Yangtze River based on the strength of its
basic industries, according to Panzhihua Mayor Qin Wanxiang.
</P>
<P>
Panzhihua, famous for Panzhihua Iron and Steel Co. and Ertan
Hydropower Station, is home to 20 percent of China's iron
reserves, 64 percent of vanadium reserves and 93 percent of
titanium reserves. Vanadium and titanium are rare minerals used by
the iron, coal, military and aerospace industries.
</P>
<P>
The central government listed the construction of Panzhihua as
a major strategic policy in the early and mid-1960s. At that time,
there were only seven households at the place. The goal was to
adjust China's industrial layout and promote economic advancement
by exploring rich mineral resources in the locality.
</P>
<P>
The city, founded 32 years ago, has sold more than 50 million
tons of iron, steel, electromechanical and building materials,
with last year's steel output hitting 2.8 million tons and iron
3.3 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Second-stage construction of Panzhihua Iron and Steel Company,
which commenced in 1986 and is scheduled for completion by the end
of this year, involves the installation of furnaces, and
continuous casting and sheeting equipment. Completion of the
project will raise the company's annual production capacity for
iron, steel and sheeting materials by one million tons each.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the 240 meter Ertan Hydropower Station dam is
scheduled for completion in the near future. The station, located
in the lower reaches of the Yalong River, will have a combined
generating capacity of 3.3 million kw and will generate 17 billion
kw/hours of electricity annually. The project is being constructed
at a cost of 33 billion yuan, with the first set generators
expected to enter operation in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
Panzhihua is preparing to construct a new airport, said the
mayor, adding that future plans call for the city to electrify the
Chengdu-Kunming Railway Line, rebuild highways and bridges, and
install a modern telecommunications network.
</P>
<P>
The city will continue to develop heavy industry in conjunction
with establishing more bases to produce farm and sideline
commodities. The bases will offer "high yields, high quality and
high efficiency", and will serve as centers for scientific and
technological information, finance, trade and commerce, said Qin.
</P>
<P>
Panzhihua will celebrate its 50th Anniversary in the year 2015,
and by that time will have achieved 41 billion yuan in GDP and a
per capita GDP of 34,000 yuan, which will reach the standards of
the world's moderately developed countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiaolangdi Dam to Tame Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Yellow River, China's
second longest river, has for years loomed perilously over cities
at elevations below the river bed, including Zhengzhou, capital of
Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
One Chinese hydrologist noted that the completion of the
Xiaolangdi dam and reservoir project on October 31 will
effectively mitigate catastrophic flooding. It will raise the
flood prevention capacity along the river from the current 60 year
flood to a 1,000 year flood.
</P>
<P>
Xiaolangdi, located 40 km from Luoyang, Henan Province, will
have a storage capacity of 12.65 billion cubic meters. Main
structures include 10 intake towers, nine flood and sediment
tunnels, six power tunnels, an underground power house and a
rock-filled dam.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, the world's muddiest river in the world,
carries over 1.6 billion tons of sand annually, with each cubic
meter of water containing 35 kg of sand, 69 times levels in the
Yangtze River. The river bed rises 10 cm (four inches) annually
due to silting.
</P>
<P>
As a result, dikes along the river have been breached on 1,500
occasions and the river has changed course 26 times over the past
2,500 years dating back to the Warring States Period (475-221 BC).
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government has allocated vast amounts of material,
funding and manpower since the founding of New China in 1949 to
reinforce 1,300 km of embankments along the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
People living in areas along the Yellow River have reclaimed
156,000 sq. km. of eroded land since the end of 1995, or a third
of the total land area scheduled for reclamation. Over 316,000
sq. km of eroded land, or 73 percent of the total, will be
reclaimed by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir will also have the capacity to store 7.6 billion
cubic meters of silt flowing from upstream. The fact that the
river bed will remain stable for 20 years will save the state vast
amounts of funds and materials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Greenpeace Sinks Coca Cola's Advert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A million U.S. dollars
advertisement for Coca Cola, which has been on Lebanon's TV only
for a month, has been withdrawn since its slogan was considered as
a wrong message to the consumers, local newspaper the Daily Star
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Fouad Hamdan, member of Lebanon's environment group Greenpeace,
said the advertisement featuring one-way plastic bottles and its
slogan "Drink it and don't return it" could be understood
as encouraging people to aggravate Lebanon's waste crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said that the use of non-returnable plastic bottles was
making an already serious waste problem worse and that
authorities were not "even thinking about introducing plans based
on waste reduction, separation at source and then recycling."
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, he said, Coca Cola "had responded very positively
to our comments and decided to change it."
</P>
<P>
Pierre Haddad, general manager of Fortune Promo-Seven Beirut,
the advertizing company that handles Coca Cola, said that the
intention behind the advertisement had been "to answer in a
marketing way to a specific campaign by Pepsi" which sports
the slogan "Drink it and return it."
</P>
<P>
"Pepsi already has two thirds of the market, the majority of
which is in non-returnable packaging, and our 15 percent share
would not have added to the problem," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Uganda's Coffee Exports Reaches Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Uganda exported 4.15 million
bags of coffee in the 1995/96 season, reaching a record high in
the country's history of coffee industry and surpassing the
exports of 3.7 million bags recorded during the 1972/73 season.
</P>
<P>
Coffee has been Uganda's biggest foreign exchange earner,
covering 65 percent of the country's export income while the
figure in 1988 is 95 percent when the country started to
diversify its economy as part of a broad economic reform package.
</P>
<P>
Uganda earned 388 million U.S. Dollars from last season's
coffee export.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's total coffee output declined from 174,000 tons in
1989 to 168,000 tons in 1990 due to the price fall caused by the
breakdown of the quota system on coffee in July 1989 when Brazil,
a major coffee producer, clashed with central American countries
on the quota.
</P>
<P>
The figure for the 1993/94 season rose to 180,000 tons or
three million bags (60 kilograms per bag) and then 4.2 million
bags for the 1995/96 season.
</P>
<P>
The significant rise of coffee production or exports (Uganda
exports most of its coffee produced yearly) in recent years is
attributed to a number of measures taken by the Ugandan
government in a bid to promote its coffee production.
</P>
<P>
The government has set up three task forces to review the
coffee production, marketing and export systems. Based on their
recommendations, the Uganda Coffee Development Authority (UCDA)
revised its relevant regulations on the coffee production and
export so as to make them more responsive in the coffee industry
and its regulatory functions.
</P>
<P>
Besides, privatization of the coffee nurseries was initiated
to increase the production of coffee seedlings so as to speed up
replacement of low yielding coffee trees at reasonable costs to
farmers.
</P>
<P>
With the introduction of prolific variety called a clonal
coffee, Uganda's coffee production has increased by a wide
margin. The clonal coffee has a yielding capacity of three tons
per hectare compared to the robusta coffee with a yield of 1.2
tons per hectare.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise of coffee earnings is attributed to the coffee
retention system introduced by the world's coffee production
countries in October, 1993 and the liberalization of the export
system on the national level.
</P>
<P>
The retention system has helped the rise of coffee price from
84 U.S. Cents to 2 Dollars per kilogram since African coffee
producers adopted in August 1993 a new policy which stipulates a
20 percent reduction of coffee exports.
</P>
<P>
Liberalization of the export system has removed export
monopoly from the Coffee Marketing Board Ltd and today over 80
companies in the country have been licensed to export coffee.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the rise of earnings is that the interest
in Uganda's coffee worldwide has been boosted by the Uganda
coffee home page on internet, which was fully developed last year
with the support from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
As for the future of Uganda's coffee production and exports,
the Uganda Coffee Farmers' Association (UCFA) has decided to
double the country's current annual coffee production of 4.2
million bags during the years 1996-2001.
</P>
<P>
The measures for realizing this target have also been worked
out. They are to improve the quality of coffee, increase its
yield and export directly at least 30 percent of the production
into specialty market as well as establish extension service in
all major coffee-growing countries.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the UCFA will develop an efficient and functional
information system between the coffee farmers and all its
structures and other relevant organizations in the coffee sub
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Clean Environment of Forbidden City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital plans to
invest more than 200 million yuan (24 million US dollars) into a
massive renovation project for the Forbidden City in the heart of
downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
An ancient city moat surrounding the complex of imperial
buildings will be dredged, and all of some 480 sewage outlets
along the waterway will be closed in order to prevent the water
from becoming polluted.
</P>
<P>
All the residential dwellings between the waterway and the
compound wall will be dismantled as residents and units gradually
move out. Units occupying some houses, which are cultural relics
under the top state protection, will also be asked to relocate.
</P>
<P>
The whole project, called "To Bring A Complete and Beautiful
Forbidden City to the 21st Century," will be completed by the year
2000. It was initiated by some noted relics protection experts in
Beijing, and will be jointly carried out by local relics
protection authority and district governments.
</P>
<P>
The Forbidden City neighboring Tian'anmen Square is one of the
most popular tourist spots in Beijing. It served as the imperial
residence during the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911)
dynasties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
