<HEADLINE> China Improving Economic Efficiency By Setting up Company Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- China's strategy to improve the
efficiency of its state-owned enterprises by establishing more
big-name company groups has been successful, with eastern coastal
areas charting the most progress, the People's Daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Big company groups have reported good economic returns. In
Shanghai, a prominent industrial city on China's east coast,
large-scale enterprises which account for only three percent of
the all industrial enterprises there generate nearly 55 percent of
the city's total industrial output value and 76 percent of its
total pre-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
City officials have pledged to get several local conglomerates
listed among the world's top 500 companies by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu Province, an economic powerhouse in east China, has
been experiencing a higher growth in heavy industrial development
since the beginning of the 1990s, and has been working to ensure
the planned establishment of the province's 21 major enterprise
groups.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Province, Jiangsu's neighbor on the coast, has been
creating conditions to help form a coalition of efficient
enterprises through joint financing and development of common
products.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that these inter-regional company groups
have been given more decision-making power in business, which has
improved economic efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese market has become increasingly closely linked to
the world market since the country opened to the outside world in
1979.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that half of the world's top 500 companies have
broken into the Chinese market. Many domestic conglomerates have
learned how to compete as a result of their competition with
trans-national companies.
</P>
<P>
Big Chinese company groups such as the Chunlan Group and Panda
Group of Jiangsu, Lizhu Group of Zhuhai in Guangdong Province, and
Hai'er Group of Shandong Province, have become well-known
in China.
</P>
<P>
Hai'er Group, one of China's leading manufacturers of
refrigerators and other household electrical appliances, has
acquired a dozen enterprises of different kinds across the country
to form a conglomerate with some 100 enterprises as its members,
thereby increasing its assets to 3.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Its products are sold in more than 40 countries. The group
chalked up 6.2 billion yuan in sales and generated 500 million
yuan in pre-tax profits in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
