<HEADLINE> World Bank to Release 62 Million Dollars to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank, now comfortable
with the Zimbabwean government's plans to restore fiscal
discipline, has approved the release of the second tranche of
about 62.5 million U.S. Dollars to its reform program.
</P>
<P>
The bank's deputy resident representative Kapil Kapoor told
journalists on Thursday that the bank was pleased with the
general direction of reforms during the past few months.
</P>
<P>
The tranche would provide the government with the much needed
budgetary support to assist fiscal reform efforts in various
sectors, including trade liberalization, agricultural reform,
investment deregulation, transport sector deregulation and the
commercialization of parastatals.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the central government budget, he said that the
expenditure control system put in place two years ago was
beginning to work.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the bank is now of the opinion that good progress
has been made in turning the fiscal situation around."
</P>
<P>
Following a detailed public expenditure review, the budget
announced last month for 1997/98 was aimed at further
consolidating the fiscal situation, and the government reiterated
its commitment toward fiscal reform.
</P>
<P>
Kapoor said with such positive developments like privatization
of state-owned enterprises, tightening of tax administration and
decisions to establish an independent revenue authority had made
the bank to start discussions with the Zimbabwean government on
supporting the next phase of reforms. 
