<HEADLINE> Canadian Firm to Set up Titanium Processing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian company, Tiomin
Resources Inc., is to set up a titanium processing factory in
Kenya's second largest city of Mombasa, following the discovery
of large deposits of the mineral at the Coast Province.
</P>
<P>
Anton Esterbuizen, the firm's exploration manager, said here
this week that the construction of the factory, to be based at
Dongo Kundu near the Indian Ocean harbor, will start in June next
year and get raw materials from mines in Kwale District.
</P>
<P>
The company will invest around 100 million U.S. Dollars to
start the processing, which is said to be capable of raising over
400 jobs for Kenyans in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
He also assured that the mining of titanium would not be
harmful to the environment of the east African country and the
land could be used later for cultivation.
</P>
<P>
High-grade zones of titanium-bearing sand have been identified
at Kenya's Indian Ocean coast and also believed to contain
combined rutile and zircon whose grade approaches 0.5 percent.
Titanium is used by paper, food and paint industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
