<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Attack Copter Sale Dismissed by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish government has
dismissed a report that Turkey had asked South Africa to supply
its army with 12 Rooivalk attack helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Local media today quoted a statement issued by Turkish embassy
in Pretoria as saying that Turkey's embargo against South Africa
still stands, not only for helicopters, but for all defense
materials.
</P>
<P>
Turkey recently announced a tender for the manufacturing of a
number of helicopters locally.
</P>
<P>
"South African manufacturers were not and will not be invited
to participate in the tender," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The South African government last week had blocked the sale of
Rooivalk helicopters to Turkey on "human rights and political
grounds", according to the report.
</P>
<P>
South Africa lifted its arms embargo against Turkey in April,
which was imposed in 1995 in the wake of a massive incursion by
the Turkish army into neighboring northern Iraq to hunt down
separatist Turkish Kurds who had bases in the area.
</P>
<P>
However, South African Foreign Ministry said all future
applications for the sale of arms to Turkey would be dealt with
"on a case to case basis". 
</P>
</TEXT>
