<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Keeps Away from Controversial Shrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto did not visit the controversial Yasukuni Shrine today,
the 52nd anniversary of Japan's surrender in World War II.
</P>
<P>
The shrine, which houses the memorial tablets of 14 class-A war
criminals including Japan's wartime prime minister Hideki Tojo and
other Japanese military personnel, is a symbol of militarism in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's visit to the shrine last year attracted severe
criticism from Japan's neighboring countries and forced him to
announce that he would not visit the shrine any more while in
office. 
</P>
