<HEADLINE> Argentina Cashes in Exodus of Footballers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Argentina broke all records
in first seven months this year by exporting 345 football players
abroad, pumping around 30 million US dollars into its football
clubs' treasury.
</P>
<P>
The major transfer, of course, was that of Argentine
international Ariel Ortega from River plate to Valencia for 9
million US dollars, which is a record for an Argentinian club.
</P>
<P>
Argentine players, running around Europe from the northern
Finland to southern Greece, enjoy good reputations in the
soccer-mad continent, but the biggest Argentine exporters flocked
to their neighbouring Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
Last month's transfer market saw Mexico hit the top by snapping
up 33 Argentine footballers, followed by Bolivia with 20 and
Paraguay with 19.
</P>
<P>
Argentine clubs last year contributed around 50 million US
dollars net income to the government's foreign revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
