<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu again
lashed out Thursday at the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
for failing to crack down on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a graduation ceremony in the National Defense
College, Netanyahu sharply criticized the Oslo accords, which he
said have enabled terrorists to establish themselves in sheltering
cities in the Palestinian territories. (Israel-Palestine-Netanyahu)
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The United Nations Secretary General's special
representative Lakhdar Brahimi today expressed optimism about the
settlement of the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
On his arrival at Islamabad International Airport this morning,
Brahimi told the press that peace in the war-torn country had to
come from Afghans themselves.
</P>
<P>
"We've to be optimistic and it depends very much on the parties
 concerned," he said. (Pakistan-UN-Afghanistan)
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian President Kocheril Raman Narayanan and
Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral today have called for a new
movement against corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation on the occasion of the 50th anniversary
of India's independence from British colonial rule, the president
said that corruption was corroding the vitals of politics and
society and asked the people to be in the forefront of the fight
against corruption, casteism and criminalization of politics.
(India-Golden Jubilee-Address)
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia's Supreme Defense Council is determined
to strengthen security and supervision along areas bordering
Albania, the official Tanjug news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the military press office said that the
number of Albanian people illegally entering Yugoslavia has
increased recently and some of them may be involved in organized
terrorist activities. (Yugoslavia-Albania-Border)
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia's recession has been curbed and the country's
economy is showing signs of improvement, Russian Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, Russia's gross domestic
product (GDP) was 99.8 percent as that of the same period in 1996,
while industrial output achieved an increase of one percent,
Chernomyrdin told Itar-Tass news agency. (Russia-Economy)
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States will start rotating and soon
increase the number of troops deployed in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Troop rotation begins today and the number of troops will
increase from 8,000 to 11,000 during the Bosnian elections, said a
Pentagon spokesperson Thursday. (U.S.-Bosnia-Troops) 
</P>
</TEXT>
