<HEADLINE> Mugabe Happy with Progress in Congo Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe has
commended the Congolese government for accepting the formation of
a transitional government as a positive move that will facilitate
elections in the troubled Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
In a message to Congolese President Pascal Lissouba, the
Zimbabwean leader said on Thursday that he had been informed of
"significant" progress in the negotiations to end the crisis in
Brazzaville by secretary-generals of the U.N. and the OAU, Kofi
Annan and Salim Ahmed Salim respectively.
</P>
<P>
"I urge you to persevere in your magnanimity in the interest
of compromise and reconciliation that will restore peace,
democracy and stability to Congo," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "we all count on your continued determination and
understanding to agree on viable transitional arrangements in
order to find a speedy solution to the crisis in your country."
</P>
<P>
He also sent a similar message to former Congolese strong-man
Denis Sassou Nguesso whose militia have been fighting government
forces for more than two months.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean leader who is also thae current chairman of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), equally commended Gabonese
President Omar Bongo for his "untiring fforts" in his capacity
as chairman of the International Mediation Committee.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe's messages also followed an announcement on Wednesday
by central African leaders of a peace initiative for Congo which
he will spearhead.
</P>
<P>
Fighting in Congo (B) resumed in earnest last week ending a
tenuous cease-firae that had held since mid-July amid reports the
clashes have claimed some 4,000 lives. 
</P>
