<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Animal Attacks in Central China Present New Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Crops on China's Shennong Shelf, a
mountainous area known for reports of "big foot" sightings in
Hubei province, are facing a new threat now -- wild animal
damage.
</P>
<P>
For hundreds of years, farmers there lived on farming and
hunting and were plagued by droughts, hail, insects, and other
natural disasters. Then, beginning in the 1970s, the shelf's
ecology caught the attention of environmentalists who called on
the local government to protect the animals there, and now a new
burden has been added as the result of wild animal protection
regulations.
</P>
<P>
When the farmers gave up their guns for hunting they took to
looking after the wild animals. Eventually however, wild pigs,
bears, and rhesus monkeys turned to "robbery", raiding the
farmers' fields for corn and sweet potatoes, their major crop, at
night.
</P>
<P>
To drive the wild animals away from the crops they put up
scarecrows and set off firecrackers in iron pails. But after a
while, all these tricks failed, and the farmers could do nothing
but watch as the wild animals ran free.
</P>
<P>
To compensate the farmers, the local government has had to
offer a large sum of money as aid to the victims of this odd
"calamity".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
