<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Continues Attacking PNA on Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu again lashed out Thursday night at the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) for failing to crack down on
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a graduation ceremony of the National Defense
College, Netanyahu sharply criticized the Oslo accords, which he
said have enabled terrorists to establish themselves in
sheltering cities in the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that in the past four years since the signing of
Oslo accords, the PNA has not acted to fight terrorism. At the
same time, he added, extremist groups such as the Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) and Islamic Jihad have grown stronger
and used Palestinian towns to launch attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The hardline premier said he still wanted to continue the peace
process if the PNA would fulfill its commitments to fighting
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's attacks came immediately after the four-day shuttle
mission here by U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross, who said
having succeeded in reviving the stalled Israeli-Palestinian
security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials have been critical of Ross' biased
position in mediation which was in favor of Israel's insistence on
the PNA's fighting terrorism but neglected the Palestinian demand
for an end to Israeli sanctions imposed after the July 30 suicide
bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Hamas claimed responsibility for the attack, which killed 16
people and wounded 170 others. Israel has yet to prove the
authenticity of the claim.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli response included a total closure on the
Palestinian self-rule territories, and suspension of transfer of
tax revenues to the PNA. Since the PNA has agreed to resume
security cooperation with Israel, it remained doubtful if such
collaboration will be effective when the sanctions are still
intact.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat strongly condemned Thursday the
continued Israeli sanctions, saying Netanyahu was fighting the
Palestinian people instead of the terrorists. He vowed that the
Palestinians would never bow to any humiliation and sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Tension between Israel and the PNA has been rising since Israel
began building the controversial Har Homa settlement in East
Jerusalem last March, which led to the prolonged deadlock in the
peace talks. The situation was further aggravated by the suicide
bombings in Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market, which erased
glimmering optimism over a quickened resumption of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel is insisting the PNA launch a long-term fight against
terrorism as a precondition for lifting its sanctions and
resuming the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
