<HEADLINE> Sudanese President Ready to Talk with Garang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar el
Bashir has said he is preparing to hold peace talks with the
southern Sudanese faction leader John Garang, according to a
"East African Standard" report today.
</P>
<P>
During a stop-over at the Jomo Kenyatta International Airport
on Thursday, he said his mission to visit southern African
countries was aimed at urging other African nations to facilitate
the peace process in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese president en route to Khartoum stressed that the
Inter-governmental Authority for Development (IGAD) still plays a
major role in peace negotiations in his country.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to South Africa, Bashir said, he briefed
President Nelson Mandela on preparation of a meeting for peace
between the IGAD and Garang who heads the Sudanese People's
Liberation Army (SPLA) in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA has fought in southern Sudan since 1983 for greater
autonomy of the Christians from the Moslem north and now is
allied with armed opposition groups in northern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Bashir also briefed Mandela on the outcome of the Khartoum
Peace Agreement passed in Nairobi after a two-day summit attended
by five heads of state in the region.
</P>
<P>
At the Nairobi Summit held last month, the Sudanese government
expressed its willingness to accept the Declaration of Principles
drafted by the IGAD in 1994 as the basis for peace negotiations
in Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
