<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Now World's Third Largest Energy Producer (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Once labeled one of the
bottlenecks of China's economic development, the energy industry
after a five-year buildup has become the power behind the
country's overall economic growth.
</P>
<P>
China is now the world's third-largest energy producer,
according to a report recently released by China's State
Statistics Bureau (SSB) which also said that the country has built
up a comprehensive energy production system and formulated
effective energy policy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the status of the energy industry as one of the
basic industries supporting the national economy has been
elevated, and the once limited energy supply has been increased.
</P>
<P>
China invested heavily in its energy sector between 1992 and
1996, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The state units during the past five years invested 970 billion
yuan in fixed assets in the sector. The capital construction
investment in the period totaled 779 billion yuan. A total of
9,476 energy projects have been put into operation and some 489.3
billion yuan was added to the fixed assets of the sector.
</P>
<P>
The energy supply also showed marked improvement in the period;
China's energy production registered an average growth of 4.64
percent. The amount of energy produced in 1996 alone was
equivalent to 1.3 billion tons of standard coal, up 25 percent
from 1991.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China's coal mining capacity increased to 171
million tons. The coal output in 1996 reached 1.4 billion tons, a
net increase of 310 million tons over the figure in 1991, or a
rise of 28.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Coal production of collective and private coal mines since 1993
has exceeded that of the state-run mines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Now World's Third Largest Energy Producer (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's oil drilling capacity increased 48.51 million tons
while the natural gas exploration capacity posted a rise of 2.7
billion cubic meters. An additional 730 million tons of oil
reserve and 95.2 billion cubic meters of natural gas were
confirmed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The crude oil output in 1996 reached 157 million tons, ranking
fifth worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Offshore oil and natural gas exploration also progressed
significantly. In the offshore fields, 104 million tons of oil
reserve was confirmed while the natural gas reserve added 68.5
billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The development of the electricity industry stayed on the fast
track. China in the past five years added power generation units
with a combined capacity of 126 million kw. The installed
generation capacities till the end of 1996 totaled 237 million kw,
ranking second in the world.
</P>
<P>
China last year generated 1,081 billion kwh of electricity, a
rise of 59.6 percent over 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project, the world's largest hydropower
endeavor, is now underway and is considered a milestone in China's
hydropower development.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that China's energy development in the
future should still concentrate on electricity and be based on
coal. More efforts will also be made to develop hydropower and
high-quality fuels such as oil and natural gas. The development of
nuclear power should by then be put on the country's agenda.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the sustained economic growth in the future, the
energy supply should be increased correspondingly, the report
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that China's energy demand in 2000 may reach
1.45 billion tons of standard coal. The output of coal should hit
1.5 billion tons; the turnover of crude oil, 170 million tons;
natural gas, 30 billion cubic meters; and hydro-electricity, 240
billion kwh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Community Services Blossom in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Sifang District Neighborhood
Committee in the east China port city of Qingdao has installed
electric alarms in the homes of over 70 elderly people, with
members of the committee responding immediately to emergencies.
</P>
<P>
For example, Liu Yujie, a 69-year-old woman suffering from
cerebral thrombosis, fell and committee members responded
immediately to provide emergency assistance when summoned by her
elderly and infirmed husband.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs has prioritized assisting the
elderly in an effort to promote the country's community
services. Well over two million elderly people like Liu throughout
the country have received various forms of assistance from
neighborhood committees.
</P>
<P>
Many young people have joined the "help-the-elderly campaign"
by volunteering to be "sons" or "daughters" of elderly
people. Their efforts have enabled many elderly people living
apart from their own children enjoy family happiness.
</P>
<P>
The government encourages and fully supports community service
agencies which fulfill the needs of local residents, according to
Bai Yihua, director of Social Welfare Department of the Ministry
of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The main job of neighborhood committees is to provide services
for residents, said Bai, adding that all members of a community
are involved in the service designed to assists residents in need.
</P>
<P>
"Community services were first introduced in 1987 and have
since played an important role in serving the people and
maintaining social stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, services have been expanded from
assisting people with special difficulties to all members of a
community. The goal of community services centers have evolved
from simply helping those in trouble to developing and improving
the quality living conditions and environment for local
residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0172 </DOCNO>
