<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Community Services Blossom In China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of people involved in providing community services
has grown rapidly throughout the country. There were more than
5,000 community service centers and 260,000 smaller neighborhood
service centers in place at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that more than 5,500 service
organizations and over four million volunteers are involved in
the work.
</P>
<P>
The most common form of service is the mutual assistance
provided by neighbors, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
Most neighborhood committees in Qingdao, Shandong Province,
have established mutual aid groups which provide dinner for
schoolchildren, and set up bookstores for children and vegetable
stores for the convenience of the local community. Experts note
that related activities, regardless of their simplicity, have
helped to solve a number of problems for local residents.
</P>
<P>
"People in trouble used to turn to the government or their
employers for help, " according to Xu Guoliang, deputy-director of
the Shandong University Social Economic Development Research
Center.
</P>
<P>
However, Xu pointed out that development of a market economy
and improved community services have prompted more people to
approach their neighborhood committee or community service center
for assistance.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the deepening of China's urban reform,
combined with changing family and population structures, will make
a number of problems more evident, such as providing daily
necessities for the elderly, assisting the disabled and employing
displaced workers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the improving living standards of urban residents
and their views concerning consumption and lifestyles will create
greater demand for community services.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has decided to redouble efforts to
promote community services. Government plans call for the
establishment of service centers in more than 85 percent of the
country's over 5,600 neighborhoods by the year 2000, and to form
volunteer service groups in more than 50 percent of the country's
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
The number of volunteers involved in the work is projected to
double to eight million by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
