<HEADLINE> Chinese Millionaire-Farmer Spends Million Yuan on Wasteland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- In a rare twist, a Chinese
millionaire-turned-farmer has spent 1.6 million yuan to cultivate
nearly 100 ha of barren hillside in his hometown of Zhongning
County, located in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in northwest
China.
</P>
<P>
Ye Tingzhu, 37, made a fortune in the past decade from his
successful transportation business. Early last year, he went to
Mingsha Township in Zhongning County from the city of Yinchuan,
the region's capital, to start a new adventure.
</P>
<P>
"Agricultural development needs a long period of time and means
a lot of hardship. But I'm still young, and just won't believe I
cannot make a career out of farming," answered Ye, when relatives
asked him about his "foolish" notion of making money from farming.
</P>
<P>
He employed some technicians to work out a cultivation plan,
and built a 2.4-km water diversion project at the foot of the
Xiejiatang hills, where the once-barren hillside is now covered
with greenery.
</P>
<P>
Because of the shortage of money, he sold his car to buy a high
lift pump this spring. He stayed in the mountains for a whole
month to oversee the construction.
</P>
<P>
Ye also spent tens of thousands of yuan harnessing a valley so
that the villagers in his hometown could protect their farmland
from flooding.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious young farmer plans to open up another 200 ha of
wasteland in three years to further develop agriculture, and also
plans to experiment with forestry and animal husbandry projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
