<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Students Down on Farm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Yang Shengxue, 13 years old, a
city kid and the only daughter in her family, is spending her
summer vacation on a farm to learn how to plant rice and raise
sheep.
</P>
<P>
For urban youths who want a hands-on experience of the farming
life, a special farm was recently built in Cha'an village, Hongqi
Town, Ganjingzi District, in the suburbs of Dalian, a port city in
northeast China's Liaoning Province. The farm has dorms with 200
beds and one-hectare of cultivated land. The construction of the
farm cost 830,000 yuan (about 104,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
More than 20 varieties of crops, such as rice, cotton and
peanuts, are grown there and several hundred head of livestock
raised.
</P>
<P>
The young people say they get a kick out of the sheep, rabbits
and ducks, and for the first time in their life have seen wells,
methane-generating pits and wind-driven generators.
</P>
<P>
During their one-week stay, the students are organized to visit
vegetable-growing areas, work in the fields, and learn about
agricultural technology.
</P>
<P>
Shao Jungong, one of the teachers, said, "We want the students
to come here and experience the hard work of the farmers."
</P>
<P>
When Yang was at home, she did no housework and was treated as
a "little empress," a common occurrence in Chinese families since
the country launched its one-child policy about two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
"Before I came here, I had never thought about how the rice
comes into my bowl. Now that I've experienced the farmers' hard
work, I'll never take it for granted," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
On the farm, every 20 students share a room. They are required
to eat the same food as the local farmers and are forbidden to buy
snacks in the nearby shops.
</P>
<P>
"Every day we have to carry water from the well to our dorms,
and so we try to save every drop of water. After I go back home,
I'll never waste water again," Yang added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
