<HEADLINE> Peace Has to Come From Afghans: UN Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Secretary
General's Special Representative, Lakhdar Brahimi, today expressed
optimism about the settlement of the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
On his arrival at Islamabad International Airport this morning,
Brahimi told the press that peace in the war-torn country had to
come from Afghans themselves.
</P>
<P>
"We've to be optimistic and it depends very much on the parties
concerned because Afghanistan is the responsibility, in the first
place, of the people of Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi is on a mission to assess the Afghan situation for the
UN's further actions for restoration of peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that the neighbors of Afghanistan were also concerned
about its situation and willing to help.
</P>
<P>
"But we will examine the situation first," he said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi said that he would hold talks here with leaders of
Pakistan and exchange views with them on how the UN can best move
forward vis-a-vis resolution of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet with Afghan leaders in and outside
Afghanistan, according to the UN envoy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
