<HEADLINE> Indian Leaders Call for Movement Against Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Both President Kocheril Raman
Narayanan and Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral today have called
for a new movement against corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation on the occasion of the golden jubilee of
the country's independence of the long-standing British colonial
rule at the Central Hall of Parliament at mid-night Thursday, the
president said that corruption was corroding the vitals of
politics and society and asked the people to be in the forefront
of the fight against corruption, casteism and criminalisation of
politics.
</P>
<P>
He said that a social movement or a widespread national
movement was needed to cleanse the system.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation from the ramparts of Red Fort here this
morning, the prime minister came down heavily on prevailing
corruption and appealed to the countrymen to join hands in
beginning a new movement against it and take oath not to pay any
bribe to anybody. He termed those indulging in corruption as
"traitors" and said, "we should ex-communicate them."
</P>
<P>
Memories of the past and hopes for India's future filled the
nostalgic audience that included President K. R. Narayanan, Prime
Minister Inder Kumar Gujral and a galaxy of senior leaders and
elder citizens who gathered to celebrate the golden jubilee of
India's independence at the special session of parliament at
mid-night Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Various celebrations including processions, rallies and art
performances have been held throughout the country today.
</P>
</TEXT>
