<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 Percent of Singaporeans Want to Emigrate: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one out of every five
Singaporeans have considered emigrating to another country mainly
because of the high cost of living and a stressful life in
Singapore, according to a Straits Times survey, which is published
here today.
</P>
<P>
The Straits Times said that the 18 percent who had thought
about emigrating was up from the 15 percent who said they had
considered leaving Singapore in a similar 1989 study by
sociologists of the National University of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
A total of 477 Singaporeans were interviewed, reflecting the
general population in terms of race, age and housing types. And 85
of the interviewed said they had considered emigrating.
</P>
<P>
The survey also finds out that Australia was the top choice,
with more than one-third, or 35 percent of those who wanted to
leave Singapore considering it as a potential destination.
Malaysia was a distant second, with 13 percent, followed by the
United States, 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, conducted last month by the Singapore
Press Holdings' Research and Information Department, those who had
thought of emigrating were mainly middle-aged, better educated or
from the middle-income group.
</P>
<P>
Those between 30 and 44 years of age formed 45 percent of the
group that considered emigrating, while white collar workers
formed 60 percent of this group, with the largest proportion
earning between roughly 1,334 US dollars and 2,667 US dollars a
month.
</P>
<P>
By race, among those who had thought of leaving for another
country, 68 percent were Chinese, 19 percent Malays and 11 percent
Indian, while other races made up merely two percent.
</P>
<P>
As for the reasons for migrating, 85 percent of those who
wanted to leave said that the cost of living is too high in
Singapore; 78 percent said life is too stressful and hectic in
Singapore; 73 percent agreed that housing is expensive in
Singapore, while 72 percent said car ownership is expensive in the
Republic.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the findings, Singapore chief statistician Paul
Cheung was quoted by the Straits Times as saying that the figures
were not alarming because although more people said they were
considering emigrating, the number of those who actually do so had
not increased.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
