<HEADLINE> USAID Aids Nepal in Reducing Fertility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States Agency for
International Development (USAID) has granted Nepal 4 million U.S.
dollars for its efforts in reducing fertility and improving
maternal and child health, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
This grant to the Nepal Contraceptive Retail Sales Company
(CRSC) is part of a six-year-long, 35 million dollars worth of
efforts by the USAID and the Nepali government to lower birth
rate, improve maternal and child health and control the spread of
sexually transmitted diseases and AIDS, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978, with the USAID's support, the CRSC has been
actively promoting the use of temporary family planning methods
including condoms and pills.
</P>
<P>
These efforts have contributed to a dramatic decline in the
total fertility rate, with the average number of births by a woman
reduced from 5.6 in 1991 to 4.6 in 1996, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The CRSC has also made a range of health care products
available through its vast network of over 14,000 medical and
general outlets throughout the country, the reports added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
