<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Develop Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has formulated plans
to develop ten core areas of industry with funds from the Asian
Development Board (ADB) and the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Ministry of Science and
Technology here, the plan is to raise the manufacturing capacity
of ten industries which have shown promise at national level.
</P>
<P>
The ADB will provide an interest-free loan of 20 million US
dollars while OPEC will provide 7.4 million US dollars on
concessionary terms for the program.
</P>
<P>
The ten areas earmarked for the project are electronics,
information technology, manufacturing engineering, biotechnology,
food technology, aquaculture, environmental technology, polymer
sciences, textiles and ready-made garments, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The main aim of the program will be to improve quality so that
these products become competitive in the world market.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose centers of excellence for the 10 industries
will be set up to conduct research and train personnel.
</P>
<P>
Tea is one of Sri Lanka's main export items and the source of
25 percent of its export earnings. Total tea exports last year
recorded 244 million kg.  
</P>
</TEXT>
