<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Forced to Take Actions for IMF Aid: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Thanong
Bidaya Thursday said that Thailand was forced to implement actions
as the country needs a credit line from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Thailand has no choice but raise value added tax (VAT) from 7
percent to 10 percent, as it could not satisfy the IMF with a
small VAT hike and find another source of income, Thanong told a
local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The government also has to slash the budget to improve the
balance of payment as the country is undergoing a major economic
slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Thailand was assured with a financial aid package of 16 billion
U.S. dollars by the IMF and other economies at a meeting earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
As the IMF is expected to give a final approval for the aid
package scheduled for August 21 this year, the Thai government now
is pushing ahead measures to meet the IMF conditions, including
tax hikes, budget cut, and restructuring of the finance sector.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government also is making efforts to ease economic,
political or social disturbances caused by its decision to seek
the IMF aid within the country, which might include a cabinet
reshuffle recently.
</P>
<P>
The Thai cabinet Monday approved in principle to cut the
government budget for the 1998 fiscal year by at least another 50
billion baht (1.7 billion dollars) and is working on the details
for government agencies under the budget cut plan.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will begin to increase the VAT to 10 percent
nationwide on Saturday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
