<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Recession Curbed: Chernomyrdin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia's recession has been
curbed and the country's economy is showing signs of improving,
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said here today.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, Russia's gross domestic
product was 99.8 percent as that of the same period in 1996, while
industrial output achieved an increase of one percent,
Chernomyrdin told Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
This year's price increase totaled 9.6 percent to date, while
the July price increase only went up 0.9 percent more than the
previous month, which indicates that inflation is under control,
the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to Chernomyrdin, the retail sales index remained
unchanged compared with the same period last year, while the
number of people living below the poverty line was reduced by 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Russia's economic stability was also hailed by Russian
President Boris Yeltsin today, who was quoted by the Interfax news
agency as saying that Russia's economic reform has overcome its
problems and will not fall back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
