<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investments in Myanmar Reaches 6.2 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investments in Myanmar
reached 6.242 billion U.S. dollars at the end of June this year,
the official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
The investments, which came from 22 countries and regions,
covered 260 projects.
</P>
<P>
The five leading foreign investors are the United Kingdom,
Singapore, Thailand, the United States and Malaysia, injecting
1.318 billion, 1.215 billion, 1.132 billion, 582 million and 524
million U.S. dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Of the 11 sectors where foreign investments are involved, oil
and gas stood first with 2.192 billion U.S. dollars in 38
projects, followed by housing estate, hotels and tourism, and
mining, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report concluded that foreign investments are rising
rapidly as investors have much confidence in Myanmar's political
stability, and the nation's rich natural resources and fair labor
charges are also its advantages.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has changed to market-oriented economic system from the
centralized economic one since late 1988, opening its door to the
outside world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
