<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lei Feng: Model for Chinese Children in 1990s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A well-known Chinese hero who
died some 30 years ago is regaining popularity and is being held
up as a model for his countrymen, especially children.
</P>
<P>
Lei Feng, a People's Liberation Army soldier, gained fame
throughout China in the 1960s for his patriotism and love of the
Chinese people. He was praised by late Chairman Mao Zedong for his
unselfish deeds and plain lifestyle after he died in a traffic
accident in 1962.
</P>
<P>
A summer camp themed "Let Us Gather Around Uncle Lei Feng" was
launched this week in Fushun in northeast China's Liaoning
Province, where Lei had worked.
</P>
<P>
"Lei's spirit is not out of style -- it is the spirit of the
Chinese nation that can be inherited by our children," said Du
Xinquan, an educator.
</P>
<P>
Sun Xiaohua, headmaster of the Lei Feng Primary School in
Fushun, noted that children can learn a great deal from Lei's
legacy. "Lei has set an example for the people to love the
motherland, love work, and feel happy about helping others," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Lei's friend Qiao Anshan has given lectures about Lei in 60
cities. Following each of his reports, youngsters have crowded
around him to ask for his autograph.
</P>
<P>
A taxi driver said that Lei's story is responsible for changing
the bad habits of his "little sun" -- a Chinese term for a single
child who is spoiled by the family.
</P>
<P>
"The concept of first being a kind person and second being a
talented person has been widely accepted by the public," said Han
Li, headmaster of the Lei Feng Primary School in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the "Lei Feng spirit" has a different meaning
in the 1990s. "In the 1960s, when helping others, people were
asked to be more selfless in their lives. Now we tell the children
simply not to bother other people. If we require a child to be a
complete man, we must gradually teach him more in the future," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
