WASHINGTON -- U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch Thursday
formally sentenced Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh to death
for the truck bomb attack on the Murrah federal building that
killed 168 people in 1995.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States decided to suspend operations
at the Afghanistan embassy in Washington because of its factional
contention over who would be the representative of the country,
State Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The (State) Department has been forced to take this action
because of continuing contention among Afghan factions within the
embassy over who represents Afghanistan and our belief that there
is no effective government in the country," State Department
spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
SARAJEVO -- Bosnian Croat and Muslim officials have reached an
agreement on the return of Muslim refugees to the Croat-controlled
Jajce area, the U.N. High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The State Department on Thursday dismissed as
unfounded the charges by a congressional delegation, who, after
their visit to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK),
alleged the DPRK government had diverted food aid to the military.
</P>
<P>
"We have no indication that there has been any significant
diversion of the assistance we have provided," spokesman James
Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"As far as we are able to judge, nearly all our assistance thus
far has been directed at helping young children, particularly
children under six," he said.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi will make a six-day
state visit to Brazil from September 1-6, the Brazilian government
announced today. He will visit major Brazilian cities such as
Brasilia, Sao Paulo and Rio de Janeiro. 
