<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Gets More Funding Offers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Three more foreign firms have
offered financial assistance to the Philippines to beef up its
foreign exchange reserves following the renewed attack on the peso
and other Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Daily Inquirer reported today that Bank of Tokyo
and U.S.-based investment firms Goldman Sachs and Salomon Brothers
have informed the Philippine Central Bank of their desire to help
boost the country's gross international reserves.
</P>
<P>
This has brought to eight the number of international financial
institutions willing to assist the Philippines in beefing up its
foreign exchange reserves, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines' foreign exchange reserves, a measure of the
country's financial capability to pay for the importation of goods
and service, dropped to 9.6 billion dollars on July 18 when the
central bank intervened in the currency market to defend the peso.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that details of the funding offers by the three
firms will be submitted later.
</P>
<P>
Soon after speculative attacks forced the Philippines to
devalue its currency from 26.5 pesos against the dollar to over 29
pesos on July 11, the International Monetary Fund approved a 1.1
billion dollar loan to the country.
</P>
<P>
ABN Amro, Chase Manhattan, JP Morgan, Deutsche Morgan Grenfell
and ING Barings have also offered assistance to the Philippines,
according to the central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Daily Inquirer said that the central bank will
have to review the details of each offer before a final decision
can be made.
</P>
<P>
The peso was dragged down Thursday by fresh turmoil in Asia's
currency market. It closed at 29.44 pesos to the dollar Thursday,
down from the previous day's close of 29.05.
</P>
<P>
The peso's weakness was also triggered by a four-point cut in
the Central bank's overnight interest rates to 14 percent
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that the peso rate is still far from being
stable because of the turmoil in other Asian countries' currency
markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
