<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Extra Charges on Foreign-funded Firms Eliminated in Guangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, south China, has eliminated 60 types of illegal charges
that were being levied against foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
This was the result of a thorough investigation into existing
levies on foreign-funded enterprises, "China Daily" quoted Zhang
Wenxue, vice chairman of the autonomous region, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 60 types of charges were levied by 24 institutions. They
are considered illegal because they were instituted without the
approval of authorized departments.
</P>
<P>
Zhang reiterated that the power to assign levies rests in the
hands of the central and local governments.
</P>
<P>
However, some local departments have arbitrarily increased
levies against foreign-funded enterprises, damaging the investment
environment.
</P>
<P>
Zhang stressed that the investigation will be thorough. Those
levying charges without approval from the Central and local
governments will be strictly punished.
</P>
<P>
The region will compile and make public a list of allowable
charges, Zhang said, adding that foreign-funded enterprises will
get the same treatment as their domestic counterparts.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of this investigation, the region's price and
finance departments will issue unified charge certificates,
collector's certificates, charging notes and payment receipts.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region will also improve its supervision
mechanism by separating charging activities and supervision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
