<HEADLINE> Amazon's Water Level Drops Due to El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Amazon River's water level has
been dropping suddenly in the past two weeks probably due to the
El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian meteorologists said today that the river's water is at
110.22 meters above sea level. On August 8, it was as low as
108.39 meters.
</P>
<P>
However, the level is still higher than the record low of 107
meters registered 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The experts attributed the drop to the lack of rains in the
upper Amazon watershed and mountain range caused by the El Nino
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is a warm Pacific inshore current, which flows south
along the coast of Ecuador annually and extends down to the coast
of Peru in every seven to ten years.
</P>
<P>
There it causes an abnormal rain pattern in the Peruvian jungle
and mountain range and has a devastating effect on farming and
fishery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botanical Garden for Blind People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The provincial capital city of
Nanjing in east China's Jiangsu province is planning to create a
botanical garden that will give blind people a chance to "see" the
natural world.
</P>
<P>
On guided tours, the blind can experience the garden by
touching the plants, listening to soft music, and smelling the
fragrance of flowers, said Wang Yicheng, one of the designers from
the Nanjing Zhongshan Botanical Garden, adding that they can also
read about the plants in Braille.
</P>
<P>
"The garden will enable the blind to directly feel the
existence of nature," he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 kinds of plants are expected to be planted in the
9,000-square-meter free-to-the-public garden early next year, Wang
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
