<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investor Satisfaction In Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A recent study has found that
overseas businessmen are satisfied with the investment environment
in Beijing, Tianjin, and Shanghai, three municipalities directly
under central government control.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's biggest city, is considered more attractive
than the other two, according to the survey, done by a Shanghai
company over the phone, of 475 investors from the U.S., Japan, the
Republic of Korea and the European Community as well as Singapore,
Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
They said Shanghai is better than Beijing and Tianjin because
of its skilled people and intelligence, dense commercial
atmosphere, great market potential, high level of international
communication, and management reforms.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, the nation's capital, attracts investors because of
policy information, while Tianjin, which is two hours drive from
Beijing, has resources and a good surrounding area and convenient
living conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign businessmen are not so satisfied with property
and labor prices, efficiency of government, environmental
protection, or market studies and consultation services in the
three cities.
</P>
<P>
More than half of those surveyed described their profits as
"very good" and "good," about 38 percent said just "ok," and 60
percent want to expand investment, 30 percent want to maintain the
current level, and only 1 percent want to reduce their
investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
