<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Urges EU, U.S. to Help Resume Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and the
U.S. should shoulder their responsibilities and help the stagnant
peace process in the Middle East to resume, Austrian Prime
Minister Viktor Klima said today.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with the Austria Presse Agentur (APA),
Klima said the EU in particular should consider concentrating new
efforts on renewing the Middle East peace process as one of its
major tasks. The Palestinians, he added, have always valued the
influence of Europe.
</P>
<P>
As for Israel and Palestine, the two parties concerned, Klima
said Israel should first send a message -- no matter how weak --
to Palestine indicating that they are willing to re-build mutual
confidence and re-start peace talks.
</P>
<P>
He added that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's role in the
peace process should also be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
In a separate interview with the APA, Austrian Foreign Minister
Wolfgang Schuessel echoed the same opinion.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel said the Mideast peace talks were not mere bilateral
talks between Israelis and Palestinians; the EU and the
U.S. should participate and act as witnesses.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested the Middle East peace talks be combined with
the issues of security and economy.
</P>
<P>
As for a long-lasting peace in the Middle East, the foreign
minister listed three preconditions: guaranteed security for
Israel, extensive and constructive aid for Palestine, and the
halting of Israel's construction of a new Jewish settlement in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process stalled after Israel decided in
early March to build 6,500 Jewish homes in Har Homa, a
tree-covered hill in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economy to Expand by 7 Percent: Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
announced that its economic growth target of 7 percent for this
year can still be achieved despite the peso's recent devaluation.
</P>
<P>
In a report published here today, the National Economic and
Development Authority said that no downscaling of major economic
growth targets for this year and next year has taken place.
</P>
<P>
The planning agency was reacting to reports that it has revised
the gross national product (GNP) growth target for 1997 from 7
percent to 6.64 percent following the peso's depreciation.
</P>
<P>
No such revision has been made and the final and official GNP
targets for this year and 1998 are still 7 percent and 7.5 percent
respectively, it said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that gross domestic product will grow by 5.8
percent this year, led by the service sector, which will grow by
about 7 percent, as it continued to benefit from the
liberalization and deregulation measures implemented by the
government.
</P>
<P>
"The recent peso depreciation has minimal effects on these
targets, the net exports and net factor income from abroad are
expected to increase and are likely to offset the dampening
effects of the peso depreciation on the industry sector," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government was forced to allow the peso to float
"within a wider range" in the currency market on July 11 when the
currency was under heavy speculative attacks.
</P>
<P>
The peso has slid from 26.5 pesos to the dollar to 29.6 pesos
since then.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
