<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Labor Unions Call National Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Two Argentine labor union
confederations called for a 24-hour national strike today to
protest the country's economic situation and the labor reform
launched by President Carlos Menem.
</P>
<P>
The Transports Ministry said subway, railway, air and river
transports were functioning normally, while vehicle public
transport in the capital and the province of Buenos Aires was at
about 19 percent of normal.
</P>
<P>
The labor suspension, especially in education and transports,
has had a strong impact on the inland areas of the country,
including the provinces of Cordoba, Santa Fe, Jujuy, Tucuman,
Tierra del Fuego and Rio Negro.
</P>
<P>
The strike was called a month ago by the Movement of
Argentine Workers and the Argentine Center of Workers without the
backing of the General Workers Confederation, the main labor
organization of the country.
</P>
<P>
Today's general strike is the seventh of its kind faced by
President Menem since he assumed office in 1989.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to support the Argentine peso in the aftermath of
the collapse of Mexico's currency in early 1995, President Menem
adopted austerity measures, including severe restrictions on
public spending, which eventually resulted in a high unemployment
rate and widespread social unrest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
