<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Granted U.S. Visa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States approved a
visa for Gerry Adams, leader of the Irish Republican Army (IRA)'s
political wing Sinn Fein in Ireland, the U.S. State Department
announced today.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told a news briefing
that there will be no restrictions on fund raising while Adams is in
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Adams' visa request, lodged in Dublin on August 11, was
approved by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"He has been granted waivers in the past based on conditions of
a cease-fire. And since there is a cease-fire in place, she
granted a waiver this morning," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Since U.S. President Bill Clinton lifted a fund-raising ban in
1995, Sinn Fein has raised more than two million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Adams, 48, and senior Sinn Fein officials, who are due to
arrive here early September, are expected to raise hundreds of
thousands of dollars for the party during their visit.
</P>
<P>
Adams is expected to meet with administration officials for the
first time since an earlier IRA cease-fire ended in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
IRA, which seeks independence of Northern Ireland from British
rule, announced a new cease-fire on July 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
