<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Forum on Nanjing Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- An international forum on the
Nanjing Massacre, held to remember the 60th anniversary of the
tragedy, closed here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On August 13, 1937, Japanese aggressor troops launched a war in
Shanghai, and in December seized Nanjing, which at the time was
the capital of China. Some 300,000 people were massacred and about
one third of the city's houses were burnt down, according to Wang
Zhengsheng, secretary of the Nanjing City Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
He said that the forum was convened to review the historical
facts in a scientific and fair manner. "The Chinese people cannot
accept the fact that some Japanese have distorted the truth and
refuse to reflect on the history," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 scholars from China, Japan and the United States
attended the meeting and visited the sites were the massacres took
place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
