<HEADLINE> Chile Rejects Symbolic Alliance With United States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- In an immediate response to a
United States' proposal that would give Chile status as a
U.S. Non-NATO ally, Chilean Defense Minister Edmundo Perez Yoma
said his country rejects the idea if it means a loss of
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told
her Chilean counterpart Luis Miguel Insulza that the U.S. may
grant Argentina the "symbolic" status as a main ally outside NATO.
</P>
<P>
But the Chilean minister, who is also the country's military
chief, said on television the proposal is "far from symbolic."
</P>
<P>
The best thing the United States can do is "to continue with a
fair treatment for the southernmost countries of Latin America,
especially toward the peoples of Argentina, Brazil, and Chile," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We must know first whether an alliance with the United States
implies some kind of loss of autonomy, of which we do not fully
know the consequences," he added.
</P>
<P>
Nations already designated as close non-NATO U.S. allies
include Israel, Egypt, Jordan, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Though it does not require the U.S. to come to their aid in
times of war, nations with this status stand a better chance of
purchasing ammunition and spare parts during a conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
