<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 117,000 Year-Old Footprints Discovered in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Scientists said today that
they have discovered a set of 117,000 years old footprints of
modern humans in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The footprints were left most likely by a woman, who was
between 5.3 to 5.4 feet and walked downhill in wet sand after a
rainstorm, Lee Berger, a paleoanthropologist, told a news
conference at the National Geographic Society.
</P>
<P>
The ancient footprints, the oldest so far discovered, were
preserved in a ledge of sandstone at the edge of Langebaan Lagoon,
about 97 kilometers north of Cape Town near the Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
They were made "by a person who... looked just like us," said
Berger, who currently studies ancient life forms at the University
of Witwatersand in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
He said that raises the possibility that the person who left
footprints in the sand so long ago is an ancestor of humans living
today.
</P>
<P>
"They were made at the right time, in the right place," he
said, adding that the prints also happened to be made by a person
who carried the genetic material that would lead to the rise of
every human being.
</P>
<P>
Actually the prints were found in September 1995 by Berger and
David Roberts, a South African sand geologist.
</P>
<P>
Roberts told reporters: "The chances of finding something like
this are a million to one."
</P>
<P>
Once the prints were made they were covered very quickly
probably with windblown sand on a hillside that eventually turned
to sandstone after being buried under pressure for scores of
thousands of years, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
"They had to be buried for a very long time to turn to rock,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Three other sets of hominid footprints have been found in
Africa. Two of them were more than one million years old, too
early for modern humans. The third was made 30,000 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German, Russia Win First Titles at Euro Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Germany reapt three of the first
six medals in the European Swimming Championships with a gold and
two silvers while Russia won one gold in Seville on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Andreas Wels of Germany claimed the first title of the
championships when he won the men's one-meter springboard diving
final.
</P>
<P>
His compatriot Holger Schlepps, the 25-year-old national
champion, edged Rafael Alvarez of Spain to clinch the silver medal
with a near-perfect final dive.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Wels collected 362.10 points from his six
dives, beating Schlepps by 5.02 points while Alvarez scored 355.56
points.
</P>
<P>
Wels finished the fourth in the continental championships two
years ago and runner-up in the German nationals last month.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 10-meter platform final, Russian 17-year-old
Olga Khristoforova won the gold with 441.60 points ahead of German
Annika Walter's 438.66 and Ukrainian Svetlana Serbina took the
bronze with 438.51.
</P>
<P>
Walter conceded to the fate of a second-place finish following
her runner-up place in the same event at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
