<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Inquiry Findings Put NZ Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The findings of a long
inquiry into alleged tax evasion by some New Zealand companies
have put the coalition government in a difficult position as wide
differences have emerged in the leadership.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry, which lasted 29 months at a cost of over 12
million NZ dollars (7.7 million US dollars), was conducted by an
independent commission after allegations of tax evasion by some
big NZ companies in the deals known as the "Winebox transactions".
</P>
<P>
The allegations were made by Winston Peters, who was in
opposition at the time of filing the charges in January 1994, but
now is Deputy Prime Minister and Treasurer of the coalition
government formed last December.
</P>
<P>
He also accused the heads of Serious Fraud Office (SFO) and
Inland Revenue Department (IRD) of conspiracy, incompetence and
corruption.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the inquiry came out yesterday. But the inquiry
 commissioner concluded that no evidence of unlawful conduct,
impropriety and incompetence has been found on the part of the SFO
or IRD.
</P>
<P>
He also found that Peters' allegations against corporates and
individuals involved in the Winebox transactions to be "false and
completely unjustified."
</P>
<P>
However, after the findings were released, Peters maintained
that the report is wrong and he vowed to challenge the findings.
</P>
<P>
He also refused to apologize to the SFO and IRD heads who have
now been cleared of Peters' charges.
</P>
<P>
In Parliament yesterday, opposition parties questioned Peters'
integrity and called for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
It was also a difficult time for Prime Minister Jim Bolger. If
Peters was still an opposition leader as two years ago, Bolger
would claim victory for the government and attack his opponent
because nothing wrong was proved on the part of the government.
</P>
<P>
But now Peters is his deputy and the man he has to work
together.
</P>
<P>
Trying to distance himself from Peters, Bolger said this
morning that it is up to Peters whether to challenge the findings.
</P>
<P>
He also said in Parliament yesterday that he was delighted that
the SFO and IRD heads had been cleared of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that time ahead will not be easy for Peters.
When he raised the question of tax evasion, he was trying to upset
the then National government. By doing so, he has angered some big
companies.
</P>
<P>
No only because some people accused by him are considering
seeking compensation, but as the Treasurer in charge of NZ economy
and finances, Peters will find it hard to accomplish his job
without the support of the major businesses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970815.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
