<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Offers $2 Million Reward for Information on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States government
today offered a 2 million U.S. dollars reward for information
leading to the arrest of those responsible for four letter bombs
sent to the al-Hayat newspaper office in Washington D.C. last
January.
</P>
<P>
"It's clear to us that the people who were responsible for this
letter bomb campaign intended to conduct a terrorism campaign in
the United States and this is one of those important steps that we
can in fact take to find the perpetrators," said Greg Bujac,
director of diplomatic security at the State Department, at a
briefing.
</P>
<P>
Starting on January 2, al-Hayat at the National Press Building
in Washington received a total of four letter-bombs. The
letter-bombs were sent in the form of musical Christmas cards
which contained improvised explosive devices. Another letter-bomb
was uncovered at a post office in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that the letter-bombs appear to have
originated from Alexandra, Egypt, and were all postmarked December
21, 1996.
</P>
<P>
In addition, several letter-bombs were found in Leavenworth,
Kansas, and New York City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
