<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Industrial Production Increases in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. industrial production in
July increased by 0.2 percent following an increase of 0.3 percent
in June, the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The growth was slowed by a fall in the production of motor
vehicles and parts and smaller declines in a number of nondurable
goods manufacturing industries, the U.S. Fed said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, warmer weather and increased use of air conditioning
translated into a 1.5 percent increase in utility output.
</P>
<P>
The report said that overall output of consumer goods slipped
by 0.2 percent in July after an increase of 0.4 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
The production of nondurable goods fell by 0.3 percent
resulting from significant declines in the output of clothing,
chemical products and fuels. And the production of durable goods
was unchanged. The lack of growth in durable goods resulted from a
drop of nearly 15 percent in the production of consumer light
trucks including vans and sport untility cars.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output increased by 0.1 percent in July after a
0.3 percent increase in June. But mining output decreased by 0.3
percent, as a large gain in coal mining was more than offset by
substantial drops in other mining industries, especially the
drilling of oil and gas wells.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. industries operated at 83.1 percent of capacity, well
below a level that typically could mean inflation-causing
bottlenecks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
