<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright's Mideast Trip may be Postponed to September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright might travel to the Middle East in September, not as she
announced last week to take the trip at the end of this month,
State Department spokesman James Rubin said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"There is a possibility the trip will be in September. I
would't expect it to go much beyond that," Rubin said at a regular
briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said the timing for Albright's trip "is going to be linked to
the kind of trip she wants to have and the kind of results that we
see, in the area of security, that we're going to be watching in
the coming weeks."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the secretary of state had decided her maiden trip
to the region is "not exclusively focused on the Israeli-Palestinian
problem."
</P>
<P>
"I think it would be fair to day it will be primarily focused
on the Israeli-Palestinian problem, but we have broader interests
in the region; we have national security interests in the region
that go beyond Israel and the Palestinian Authority. So her trip
may also include a public component," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright had a long meeting with Mideast envoy Dennis Ross this
morning and they went over in some detail "what the progress and
lack thereof was in his trip," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
She has decided to "watch closely what results occur" from a
"mechanism" for Israeli-Palestinian cooperation over
anti-terrorism issues, which Ross proposed and was accepted by
Israeli and Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary ... (will) make a decision about timing for a
trip based on that assessment," Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
