<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends Reduction of UNPREDEP Forces in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today recommended to reduce the troops of the United
Nations Preventive Deployment Force (UNPREDEP) in Macedonia by
300.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security council, Annan said it was
possible to reduce the force of 1,050 by 300 soldiers starting in
October because the turmoil in neighboring Albania had subsided.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations now had to analyze what kind of
an operation was needed for Macedonia for the rest of the year and
after the troops eventually leave.
</P>
<P>
"Internally social and economic problems continue to pose a
significant threat to the country's integration and long-term
stability and further exacerbate inter-ethnic tensions", he said.
</P>
<P>
"These internal problems give rise to the question of whether
the current mandate of UNPREDEP is relevant to the present
situation and whether it can be implemented with fewer resources,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he said he was exploring "practical options
for flexible redeployment of the force" and studying what kind of
international presence was needed for the future.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Preventive Deployment Force was originally deployed to
prevent conflict elsewhere in the former Yugoslavia from spreading
over into Macedonia. It includes nearly 500 United States troops,
350 soldiers from Finland and small contingents from Indonesia,
denmark, Norway and Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
