<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees No Significant Food Aid Diversion in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The State Department on
Thursday dismissed as unfounded the charges by a congressional
delegation, who, after their visit to the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), alleged the DPRK government had
diverted food aid to the military.
</P>
<P>
"We have no indication that there has been any significant
diversion of the assistance we have provided," spokesman James
Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"As far as we are able to judge, nearly all our assistance thus
far has been directed at helping young children, particularly
children under six," he said.
</P>
<P>
The congressional delegation has just wound up its visit to the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea. The delegation said after
the visit that it saw evidence food aid may have been transferred
to the DPRK military.
</P>
<P>
But Rubin said: "We believe the World Food Program, with
experienced in-country staff, has been carefully monitoring the
distribution of assistance (and the aid) has gone to the right
places." 
</P>
</TEXT>
