<HEADLINE> UN Renews Peace Mission in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government and the
United Nations' singed an agreement today to officially renew the
UN Peace Verification Mission in the war-ridden country.
</P>
<P>
Faustino Muteka, the Minister of Administration of Territory
said after signing the agreement that the agreement would help
the implementation of the Lusaka Peace Accord signed in November
1994.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreement also indicates that the Angolan
government will push forward the peace process in the country,
through whatever means acceptable by all parties concerned,
Muteka said.
</P>
<P>
Blondin Beye, the UN official who signed the agreement, said
that the founding of the UN peace verification mission in Angola
proves that the international community believe that the Angolan
government and the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) could accomplish the work outlined by the Lusaka
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Beye said that the peace process in Angola is at a critical
moment, and what's most important is that both the government and
the UNITA should observe the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The UN peace verification team started its new mission on June
30 to supervise the implementation of the Lusaka Peace Accord in
Angola.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
