<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement Reached on Refugee Return to Jajce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Croat and Muslim
officials have reached an agreement on the return of Muslim
refugees to the Croat-controlled Jajce area, the U.N. High
Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached on Wednesday at a UNHCR-chaired meeting
in Travnik, would allow the return of 474 Muslim families
involving more than 1,000 people to return to the Jajce area,
UNHCR Kris Janowski said at a daily briefing in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
The permission of return will not only be accorded to some 500
people who were kicked out earlier this month upon their arrival
at their destroyed homes in Jajce but also those had not dared to
venture back.
</P>
<P>
One hundred families will start to return to the village of
Kruscica on Saturday, to be followed by the return of the remaining
families to other villages in the next week.
</P>
<P>
"It's good news, but again we have to wait and see whether
that happens and how it happens to tell it is successful or
not," Janowski said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
